Deadly Rift Valley fever spreading in E Cape - The Herald Online
' Deadly Rift Valley fever spreading in E Cape \n THE deadly Rift Valley fever is spreading rapidly in the Eastern Cape and has reached as close to Nelson Mandela Bay as Humansdorp and the Tsitsikamma area. \n The senior manager and director for Veterinary Services in the Eastern Cape, Dr Cedisa Mnqeta, said there were now 45 farms in the province which had tested positive for the fever and more test results were outstanding. \n There have also been eight confirmed human cases in the province. \n Rift Valley fever (RVF) can be spread to humans by handling animals and their blood, and by mosquitos. ' Meat Exports Resume, South Still Quarantined \n SOUTH Africa yesterday lifted its ban on meat imports from Namibia, but the Hardap and Karas regions remain quarantined because of an outbreak of Rift Valley fever on farms there. \nUntil yesterday, no meat from any part of Namibia could be exported. \nDr Cleopas Bamhare, the acting chief veterinary officer in the Ministry of Agriculture, Water and Forestry, yesterday said that exports from "the main abattoirs" were allowed again since yesterday. \n The ban on the movement of live animals and animal products to and from the two affected regions remained in force, he said. WHO | Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2
' WHO > \n Global Alert and Response (GAR) > \n Main content \n Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2 \nOn 11 May 2010 Bernhard-Nocht-Institute for Tropical Medicine in Germany reported that additional laboratory analyses conducted both in Germany and South Africa on the German tourist who was preliminarily diagnosed with Rift Valley Fever (RVF) following her return from South Africa, was in-fact infected with Rickettsia and not with RVF virus. 441872

HM Community News Reports
4 May 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
ReliefWeb \u00bb Document \u00bb Rift Valley fever in South Africa - update 4 ...
' Rift Valley fever in South Africa - update 4 May 2010 \n4 May 2010 -- As of 27 April 2010, German health authorities reported a laboratory confirmed case of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) in a traveller returning to Germany after a trip to South Africa from 17 March to 8 April 2010. The case, along with three travel companions, visited rural areas and game reserves along the coast of Eastern Cape and Western Cape provinces. On 7 April 2010, the case developed symptoms including fever, headache and a rash (exanthema). Almost concurrently a similar illness was reported in her travel companions. German health authorities are currently investigating the circumstances around infection in the confirmed case.\n As of 3 May 2010, the Department of Health of South Africa has reported 172 cases, including 15 deaths since the beginning of the outbreak in Free State Province, Eastern Cape Province, Northern Cape Province, Western Cape, and North West Province. While it is reported that most of these cases have had direct contact with RVF-infected livestock and/or are epidemiologically linked to farms with confirmed animal cases of RVF, there are a number of cases in which the route of transmission is currently unknown. Exposure to infected mosquitoes in these cases cannot be currently ruled out.\n The Government of South Africa has implemented public health control measures which include development of key risk reduction messages for at risk population and health worker guidelines for case identification and reporting, laboratory investigations, clinical case management, hospital infection control and the public health measures for prevention and control and animal vaccination in non-affected areas.\n WHO advises no international travel restriction to or from South Africa. However, WHO recommends that visitors to South Africa, especially those intending to visit farms and/or game reserves, avoid coming into contact with animal tissues or blood, avoid drinking unpasteurized or uncooked milk or eating raw meat. All travellers should take appropriate precautions against mosquito bites (use of mosquito nets, insect repellents). Travel medicine professionals and travel medicine services should be aware of the current RVF situation in South Africa in order to provide advice and care accordingly. ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/EGUA-855NLP?OpenDocument

News - Health: Rift Valley Fever death toll on the rise
u' \xc2\xa0 \xc2\xa0 May 07 2010 at 02:20PM \nTwo more people have died of Rift Valley Fever in the Northern Cape, while the overall confirmed cases reported to South African authorities has risen to 183, the health department said on Friday. \nHealth spokeswoman Charity Bhengu said the latest deaths were reported in Britstown and Karos, near Upington, in the Northern Cape, bringing the total deaths to 17 since the outbreak began in February. \nLaboratory confirmed human cases of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) showed 107 occurrences in the Free State, 56 in the Northern Cape, 13 in the Eastern Cape, two in the North West province and three in the Western Cape, with two unknown. \nEight people each have died after contracting the sickness in the Free State and the Northern Cape with one in the Western Cape.  ', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'North-West Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

HM Community News Reports
17 May 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Namibia
'-22.133249','17.218281',5,163
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries on Rift Valley fever outbreak in ...
'[ Speeches & statements ]\n Rift Valley fever outbreak in Namibia \n The Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries has received a notification from the Namibian veterinary authorities regarding an outbreak of Rift Valley fever (RVF) in Namibia.\n Rift Valley fever is a viral disease of animals that is spread by mosquitoes. It causes abortions in sheep, goats and cattle and can cause death in young animals. Humans can get infected if they come into contact with blood and other body fluids from infected animals, or if they assist with abortions and handle infectious aborted material, like foetuses, placentas and placental fluids.\n Hunters planning to hunt in Namibia and to bring the meat back to South Africa are advised to contact the veterinary authorities of Namibia before hunting. ', 'Namibia | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2010/10051808451001.htm

Casafree Actualit\u00e9 La fi\u00e8vre de la vall\u00e9e du Rift fait 17 morts en ...
u" Accueil Casafree : \nLa fi\xc3\xa8vre de la vall\xc3\xa9e du Rift fait 17 morts en Afrique du Sud - Sant\xc3\xa9 - Webzine\nToute l'actualit\xc3\xa9 nationale et internationale \n Monde \n Le nombre des victimes de la fi\xc3\xa8vre de la vall\xc3\xa9e du Rift s'est alourdi \xc3\xa0 17, a annonc\xc3\xa9 vendredi le minist\xc3\xa8re sud-africain de la Sant\xc3\xa9. Selon le porte-parole du minist\xc3\xa8re de la Sant\xc3\xa9, Charity Bhengu, les derni\xc3\xa8res victimes ont \xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9 signal\xc3\xa9es \xc3\xa0 Britstown et Karos, pr\xc3\xa8s de Upington, dans la province du Cap nord. L'Afrique du Sud a recens\xc3\xa9 au total 183 cas de fi\xc3\xa8vre de la vall\xc3\xa9e du Rift depuis son \xc3\xa9clatement le 13 f\xc3\xa9vrier. Huit personnes sont mortes dans l'Etat de Free, huit autres dans le Cap nord, et un dans le Cap ouest, a pr\xc3\xa9cis\xc3\xa9 le porte- parole. M. Bhengu a d\xc3\xa9clar\xc3\xa9 que la majorit\xc3\xa9 des cas humains ont eu des sympt\xc3\xb4mes de type grippal mais n'ont pas connu des complications. Les personnes qui risque de contracter la maladie sont ceux qui ont des contacts directs avec du sang ou des tissus d'animaux infect\xc3\xa9s et la majorit\xc3\xa9 des malades ont travaill\xc3\xa9 dans les fermes et les abattoirs, a-t-il expliqu\xc3\xa9. La fi\xc3\xa8vre de la vall\xc3\xa9e du Rift est une maladie virale affectant les animaux domestiques et les humains. Elle est transmise par les moustiques et autres insectes piqueurs: l'infection peut \xc3\xa9galement se produire par la manipulation de viande infect\xc3\xa9e ou des contacts avec du sang contamin\xc3\xa9.  ", 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

'4.643889','9.438611',5,12028
Yellow fever in Cameroon
u' La paciente, una estudiante de 16 a\xf1os de la escuela secundaria de Kake, present\xf3 un cuadro cl\xednico de fiebre e ictericia cuyo s\xedntoma inicial (la fiebre) apareci\xf3 el 11 de enero. La paciente, que no ten\xeda antecedentes de vacunaci\xf3n contra la fiebre amarilla y sobrevivi\xf3, fue identificada a trav\xe9s del mecanismo de vigilancia sistem\xe1tica de la fiebre amarilla. Las pruebas de ELISA realizadas en el Instituto Pasteur de Yaund\xe9 (Camer\xfan) fueron positivas para IgM, resultado confirmado mediante una prueba m\xe1s espec\xedfica (neutralizaci\xf3n por reducci\xf3n de placa) realizada en el laboratorio regional de referencia para la fiebre amarilla, el Instituto Pasteur de Dakar (Senegal).  Tras la identificaci\xf3n del caso \xedndice se realiz\xf3 en la zona una investigaci\xf3n que permiti\xf3 identificar otro caso sintom\xe1tico (con fiebre) en el que la prueba de ELISA result\xf3 negativa, al igual que en otros 50 contactos analizados.  En mayo de 2009 se realiz\xf3 en el Camer\xfan una campa\xf1a de vacunaci\xf3n masiva contra la fiebre amarilla en 62 distritos en riesgo con una poblaci\xf3n de 7,4 millones de habitantes. Sin embargo, los distritos de Kumba y Muyuka no participaron en esa campa\xf1a porque no hab\xedan tenido casos de fiebre amarilla en los \xfaltimos 50 a\xf1os. ', 'Kumba, South-West Province, Cameroon | Yellow Fever | Humans'

CBC News - U.S. oil spill could hit Atlantic tuna
'The oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico could have a serious long-term impact on tuna stocks off Atlantic Canada.\n\nThe Gulf is the spawning ground for bluefin tuna that migrate to the Atlantic region.\n\n"Many fish are going down to the Gulf to spawn," said Jackie Savitz, a marine biologist with Oceana, an international conservation group based in Washington.\n\n"The larvae of the fish is actually the most sensitive life stage to the toxic effects of oil. And one fish that\'s spawning right now down there is the bluefin tuna."\n\nThere is already concern for the health of the Atlantic bluefin tuna population. It has fallen 90 per cent since the 1970s, and the World Wildlife Fund says the species faces a serious risk of extinction. Stocks in the western Atlantic are in better shape than in the east, and the oil spill strikes at an economically important fishery in Atlantic Canada.\n ', 'Gulf of Mexico | Environmental | Humans'

Yellow fever in Cameroon
u' Le cas \xe9tait une jeune femme de 16 ans, \xe9l\xe8ve au lyc\xe9e de Kake. Elle pr\xe9sentait un tableau clinique de fi\xe8vre et d\u2019ict\xe8re. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 11 janvier, se manifestant par de la fi\xe8vre. Elle n\u2019avait jamais \xe9t\xe9 vaccin\xe9e contre la fi\xe8vre jaune et elle a surv\xe9cu. Ce cas a \xe9t\xe9 identifi\xe9 par le syst\xe8me de surveillance habituelle de la fi\xe8vre jaune.  Le Laboratoire national de l\u2019Institut Pasteur \xe0 Yaound\xe9 a mis en \xe9vidence par la m\xe9thode ELISA les IgM dans les \xe9chantillons pr\xe9lev\xe9s sur ce cas. La positivit\xe9 a ensuite \xe9t\xe9 confirm\xe9e par le test de neutralisation par r\xe9duction de plages (PNRT), un essai plus sp\xe9cifique, pratiqu\xe9 au laboratoire r\xe9gional de r\xe9f\xe9rence pour la fi\xe8vre jaune \xe0 l\u2019Institut Pasteur de Dakar (S\xe9n\xe9gal).  Apr\xe8s l\u2019identification du cas, une enqu\xeate a \xe9t\xe9 men\xe9e dans la r\xe9gion. Elle a permis de retrouver une personne symptomatique (fi\xe8vre). Les analyses de laboratoire par m\xe9thode ELISA des \xe9chantillons s\xe9riques pour cette personne et 50 autres sujets en contact ont donn\xe9 des r\xe9sultats n\xe9gatifs.  En mai 2009, le Cameroun a conduit une campagne de vaccination antiamarile dans 62 arrondissements \xe0 risque repr\xe9sentant une population de 7,4 millions d\u2019habitants. Toutefois, comme il n\u2019y avait pas eu de cas de fi\xe8vre jaune dans les deux arrondissements de Kumba et Muyuka depuis 50 ans, ils n\u2019ont pas \xe9t\xe9 couverts par cette campagne. ['<img class=\\"f\\" src=\\"..\\/hm.png\\" title=\\"HM Community News Reports\\" alt=\\"HM Community News Reports\\" \\/>', '27 May 2010', '<a href=\\"..\\/ai.php?435540&trto=en&trfr=en&pid233\\" class=\\"fbox\\">STD found in southeast NM cattle - Carlsbad Current-Argus<\\/a>', 'Other Animal Disease', '<a href=\\"javascript:sc(\'34.488400\',\'-105.996101\',5,233);\\">New Mexico, United States<\\/a>', 'Humans', 'null', 'null']

435540

HM Community News Reports
27 May 2010
Other Animal Disease
New Mexico, United States
'34.488400','-105.996101',5,233
STD found in southeast NM cattle - Carlsbad Current-Argus
u'CARLSBAD A sexually transmitted disease found in cattle has been identified in southeast New Mexico and could have potentially devastating effects on the herds of area ranches, and cattle producers are being called on to join together to combat the problem. Trichomoniasis, or "trich", is a venereal disease of cattle that does not make bulls or cows outwardly sick, but which results in the loss of reproductive efficiency of affected herds, said John Wenzel, New Mexico State University extension veterinarian. "The loss of reproductive efficiency is due to the loss of pregnancy and the lengthening of the calving season," Wenzel said. "Bulls are a mechanical spreader during the breeding season, and the infection is maintained in a herd by infected bulls and chronically infected cows called "carrier cows"." "We\'re concerned because it has been going around and it has a potential to be a major economic loss to ranchers," said Eddy County Agriculture Agent Woods Houghton. "It\'s something you can\'t solve ranch-by-ranch," he said. "The whole community has to come together." Trich has been documented in every state west of the Mississippi River and several states in the southeastern U.S., Houghton said. "New Mexico has always been one of those places that, because it\'s so dry, a lot of diseases don\'t spread," he said, but southeast New Mexico has seen an increase in the disease. To fight its spread, Houghton said agriculture officials are urging testing of potentially Advertisement \ninfected animals and promoting a program that establishes a breeding season to better monitor herds. "We\'re trying to set procedures to set up a breeding period and then get producers to test their bulls over time," he said. "We want to test them before the breeding season, after the breeding season, and then again before the next breeding season. "If we test them after the breeding season and they\'re clean, then they\'re okay," he said. Houghton said that 97 percent of cows will shed the disease if they\'re given a four- to five-month rest after breeding. Bulls can become chronic carriers, he said. "If you\'re trich-free, your average net return can be about $78 a head," he said. "With a high infestation, that could be a loss of $350 a head. "In my experience in working with ranchers, if you don\'t take care of trichomoniasis, you\'re going to lose money," he said. He noted that in this area, some fences date back to the 1930s and \'40s and are in a bad state of repair, often allowing bulls to move undetected from one herd to another. "Our livestock board has made some appropriate regulations that are not overly burdensome to producers," he said. "Working with your neighbors and testing the bulls is cheaper than repairing the fences in the long run." More information on trichomoniasis and what measures can be taken to promote its spread is available by contacting Houghton at the Eddy County Agricultural Extension office at 1304 W. Stevens St. in Carlsbad, and by calling 575-887-6595. \n\xa0\xa0\n Sentencing set today in Carlsbad district court for James Gamble \n For the Record: May 25  ', 'New Mexico, United States | Other Animal Disease | Humans'
http://www.currentargus.com/ci_15170020

['<img class=\\"f\\" src=\\"..\\/w\\" title=\\"World Health Organization\\" alt=\\"World Health Organization\\" \\/>', '27 May 2010', '<a href=\\"..\\/ai.php?435330&trto=en&trfr=en&pid12028\\" class=\\"fbox\\">Yellow fever in Cameroon<\\/a>', 'Yellow Fever', '<a href=\\"javascript:sc(\'4.643889\',\'9.438611\',5,12028);\\">Kumba, South-West Province, Cameroon<\\/a>', 'Humans', 'null', 'null']
3
435330

World Health Organization
27 May 2010
Yellow Fever
Kumba, South-West Province, Cameroon
'4.643889','9.438611',5,12028
Yellow fever in Cameroon
u"Yellow fever in Cameroon\n\n27 May 2010 -- On 25 January 2010, the Ministry of Health (MoH), Cameroon reported one case of yellow fever in Kumba district in the country's south-western region, close to the border with Nigeria's Cross River State. \n The index case was identified as a 16 year-old female student in Kake high school. She presented with a clinical picture of fever and jaundice. Onset of symptoms started on 11 January with fever. She had no history of yellow fever vaccination and survived. The index case was identified through routine yellow fever surveillance system.  Laboratory specimens from this case were found to be IgM positive by ELISA method at the National Laboratory in the Institut Pasteur, Yaound\xc3\xa9, Cameroon and confirmed positive by plaque reduction neutralization test (PRNT)- a more specific test for yellow fever- at the regional reference laboratory for yellow fever at the Institut Pasteur in Dakar, Senegal.  Following identification of the index case, an outbreak investigation was conducted in the area. The investigation identified one person as symptomatic (fever). Laboratory tests by ELISA method of serum samples for this and 50 other contact were found to be negative.  Cameroon conducted a yellow fever mass vaccination campaign in 62 at-risk-districts covering a population of 7.4 million in May 2009. The two districts of Kumba and Muyuka were however, not part of the campaign as they had no history of yellow fever cases in the past 50 years.  ", 'Kumba, South-West Province, Cameroon | Yellow Fever | Humans', 'Cross River State, Nigeria | Yellow Fever | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_27/en/index.html

Four oil-cleanup workers fall ill; Breton Sound fleet ordered back to ...
'Fishing boats helping clear oil from the Gulf of Mexico spill from Breton Sound have been called back to dock after four workers reported health problems Wednesday afternoon, Unified Command in Houma announced.\n\nCrew members on three boats reported nausea, dizziness, headaches and chest pains Wednesday about 3:30 p.m. Four workers were taken to West Jefferson Medical Center in Marrero for treatment, one traveling by air, one by boat and two by ambulance. The other crewmembers refused treatment at the dock.\n\nAs a precaution, Unified Command directed all 125 of the commercial vessels that had been outfitted with equipment for oil recovery operations in the Breton Sound area, to return to their temporary accommodations in Breton Sound.\n\n"No other personnel are reporting symptoms, but we are taking this action as an extreme safeguard," said Coast Guard Chief Petty Officer Robinson Cox, the assistant safety officer at Incident Command Post Houma.\n\nThe Coast Guard, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, the Environmental Protection Agency, and safety officers from BP are investigating the incident. Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, United States
'26.950333','-97.383591',5,8502
Gulf oil spill threatens Everglades and other parks - Green House - ...
'The Everglades National Park in Florida and the Padre Island National Seashore in Texas are among 15 "special places" most threatened by the massive Gulf of Mexico oil spill, says a report today by two environmental groups.\n\nThe oil threatens, among other wildlife, brown pelicans, whooping cranes, manatees, bottlenose dolphins and sea turtles that live in these state parks, wildlife refuges and national parks, according to the report.\n\n"This could become America\'s greatest environmental disaster," says Theo Spencer of the Natural Resources Defense Council, which co-wrote the report, adding it illustrates the dangers of U.S. "over-dependence on fossil fuels."\n\n"Because the potential reach of this catastrophe is so broad, our list certainly cannot include more than a tiny fraction of what is at stake as oil continues to gush into and spread around the Gulf," says Stephen Saunders, president of the Rocky Mountain Climate Organization, the report\'s other author. ', 'Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, United States | Poisoning | Humans', 'Everglades National Park, Florida, United States | Poisoning | Humans', 'Padre Island National Seashore, Texas, United States | Environmental | Humans', 'Everglades National Park, Florida, United States | Environmental | Humans'
http://content.usatoday.com/communities/greenhouse/post/2010/05/gulf-oil-spill-threatens-floridas-everglades-and-other-parks-refuges/1

HM Community News Reports
26 May 2010
Environmental
Barataria Bay, Louisiana, United States
'29.374111','-89.938126',5,12015
In Louisiana, wildlife shows effects of gulf oil spill
'GRAND ISLE, LA. -- In the Louisiana marsh, oil-coated pelicans flap their wings in a futile attempt to dry them. A shorebird repeatedly dunks its face in a puddle, unable to wash off. Lines of dead jellyfish float in the gulf, traces of oil visible in their clear "bells." \nThese scenes, scientists say, are confirmation of what they had feared for a month. Now that oil from the Gulf of Mexico\'s vast spill has come ashore -- in some places, as thick as soft fudge -- it is causing serious damage in one of the country\'s great natural nurseries.\n\nIn nature, oil is a versatile killer. It smothers the tiny animals that make up a coral reef. It suffocates blades of marsh grass, cutting them off from air and sunlight. It clumps up a bird\'s feathers, leaving it unable to fly. Then, trying to remove the oil, birds swallow it.\n\nFor now, scientists are seeing the worst effects only in one corner of the Louisiana coast.  ', 'Barataria Bay, Louisiana, United States | Environmental | Humans', 'Isle Grande Terre, Louisiana, United States | Environmental | Humans'
http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/26/AR2010052602509.html

Fishermen Report Illness From BP Chemicals - Health News Story - WDSU ...
'LAFITTE, La. --\nMore and more stories about sick fishermen are beginning to surface after the oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico.\n\nThe fishermen are working out in the Gulf -- many of them all day, every day -- to clean up the spill. They said they blame their ailments on the chemicals that BP is using.\n\nOne fisherman said he felt like he was going to die over the weekend.\n\n"I\'ve been coughing up stuff," Gary Burris said. "Your lungs fill up."\n\nBurris, a longtime fisherman who has worked across the Gulf Coast, said he woke up Sunday night feeling drugged and disoriented.\n\n"It was like sniffing gasoline or something, and my ears are still popping," Burris said. "I\'m coughing up stuff. I feel real weak, tingling feelings."\n\nMarine toxicologist Riki Ott said the chemicals used by BP can wreak havoc on a person\'s body and even lead to death. ', 'Lafitte, Louisiana, United States | Poisoning | Humans', 'Lafitte, Louisiana, United States | Environmental | Humans'

Report lists two Alabama parks threatened by oil spill - Birmingham ...
u' Two Alabama national parks are among the 15 most threatened by the BP  Gulf oil spill, according to a new report.\n\nBon Secour National Wildlife Refuge in Alabama\xe2\x80\x99s Gulf Shores community and Grand Bay National Wildlife Refuge, which stretches between Mississippi and Alabama, are at risk of contamination from the oil spill, according to the Natural Resources Defense Council.\n\nOther parks at risk are Everglades National Park in Florida, Padra Island National Seashore in Texas and Delta National Wildlife Refuge in Louisiana.\n ', 'Bon Secour National Wildlife Refuge, Alabama, United States | Poisoning | Humans', 'Grand Bay National Wildlife Refuge, Alabama, USA | Poisoning | Humans', 'Bon Secour National Wildlife Refuge, Alabama, United States | Environmental | Humans', 'Grand Bay National Wildlife Refuge, Alabama, USA | Environmental | Humans'

Gulf spill kills 500 turtles & seabirds | The Sun
'MORE than 300 seabirds and 200 turtles have died in the Gulf of Mexico since the oil spill, wildlife chiefs said yesterday.\n\nThey fear the death toll will soar if the huge slick is swept ashore during the upcoming hurricane season.\n\nBiggest victims are diving birds such as brown pelicans and gannets.\n\nBut songbirds and waders are increasingly at risk as the spill heads for the Louisiana beaches and marshlands.\n\nNineteen dead dolphins are also being tested for contamination.\n\nBird rescuer Jay Holcomb said: "The potential for this being catastrophic is right there because there\'s a massive amount of oil in the water."\n\nBP is about to try to cap the leaking well with mud and concrete.\n\nEleven workers killed when BP\'s rig blew up were remembered yesterday at a service in Jackson, Mississippi. Gulf Oil Spill: Fishing Ban Expanded; Endangered Turtles Threatened | ...
u'With no end to BP\xe2\x80\x99s gushing oil leak in sight, attention has turned to trying to ascertain just how damaging the spill could be for wildlife in the Gulf of Mexico. Yesterday the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) doubled the size of the fishing ban in the Gulf. Now nearly 20 percent of the water is off-limits because of the expanding oil slick.\n\nBecause so much oil is under the surface, and diluted but still dangerous, it\xe2\x80\x99s hard to get a handle on just how bad things will be. But turtles seem to be the bellwether for worries about sea life. Since April 30, marine biologists have recorded more than 150 sea turtle deaths, and while they can\xe2\x80\x99t immediately say all those were directly related to the oil spill, it\xe2\x80\x99s a much higher number of deaths that is usual for this time of the year. 434731

HM Community News Reports
26 May 2010
Poisoning
Gulf of Mexico
'25.642208','-92.460411',5,12343
Over 300 dead birds are likely Gulf spill victims | Reuters
' (Reuters) - More than 300 sea birds, nearly 200 turtles and 19 dolphins have been found dead along the U.S. Gulf Coast during the first five weeks of BP\'s huge oil spill off Louisiana, wildlife officials reported on Monday.\n\nGreen Business\n\nThe 316 dead birds collected along the shores of Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and Florida -- plus 10 others that died or were euthanized at wildlife rehabilitation centers after they were captured alive, far outnumber the 31 surviving birds found oiled to date.\n\nThe raw tally of birds listed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service as dead on arrival at wildlife collection facilities include specimens obviously tainted with oil and some with no visible signs of oil contamination.\n\nBut all are being counted as potential casualties of the oil gushing since April 20 from a ruptured wellhead on the floor of the Gulf because of their proximity in time and space to the spill, said Jay Holcomb, who directs a rescue center for birds in Fort Jackson, Louisiana.\n\nThe same is true of nearly 200 sea turtles found dead and dying along the Gulf Coast, and 19 dead dolphins verified in the region since the oil drilling blowout on April 20.\n\nTissue samples collected eventually will be analyzed to determine more conclusively if the animals were contaminated with oil from the BP spill.\n\nHolcomb, director of the California-based International Bird Rescue Research Center, said mortality for sea birds, many of them in the midst of their breeding season, is expected to climb sharply, especially if hurricanes move into the region and sweep more oil ashore.\n\n"The potential for this being catastrophic is right there because there\'s a massive amount of oil in the water, and it\'s still pouring out, and there\'s a lot of nesting birds and a lot of birds using the coast," he told Reuters. "If the tropical storms take that oil and move it, that\'s when you\'re going to see the real impact, I think."\n\nThe size of BP\'s disaster in the Gulf could eclipse the scale of the 1989 Exxon Valdez spill in Alaska\'s Prince William Sound, in which an estimated 250,000 sea birds perished.\n\nDIVING BIRDS HARDEST HIT SO FAR\n\nThe birds hardest hit by oil in the Gulf so far are those that feed by diving into the water for fish, including the Louisiana state bird, the brown pelican, removed last year from the U.S. endangered species list, and the northern gannet, Holcomb said.\n\nBut shorebirds, wading birds and songbirds will increasingly be put in harm\'s way as more oil washes onto beaches and into marshlands. ', 'Gulf of Mexico | Poisoning | Humans', 'Gulf of Mexico | Environmental | Humans'
http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE64N5L020100525
Humans
null
null

Oil spill to wipe out gulf\u2019s sperm whales? | The Daily Caller
u'If the Gulf of Mexico oil spill kills just three sperm whales, it could seriously endanger the long-term survival of the Gulf\xe2\x80\x99s native whale population, scientists say.\n\nRight now between 1,400 and 1,660 sperm whales live year-round in the Gulf of Mexico, making up a distinct population from other Atlantic Ocean groups, in which males make yearly migrations.\n\nAll sperm whales are considered endangered under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. But the Gulf of Mexico population is thought to be especially vulnerable due to its relatively small size.\n\nThe whales are now at risk from the ongoing Deepwater Horizon oil spill, because they are likely to ingest or inhale toxic crude and noxious oil fumes. (See pictures of the oil seeping into Louisiana marshes.)\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe know there\xe2\x80\x99s going to be some [oil] exposure, and we know there\xe2\x80\x99s an endangered species. If you put those two thing together, there is reason for concern,\xe2\x80\x9d said Celine Godard-Codding, an environmental toxicologist at Texas Tech University.\n\n ', 'Gulf of Mexico | Environmental | Humans'

433948

HM Community News Reports
25 May 2010
Meningitis - Neisseria
Italy
'42.795780','12.071740',5,75
Signora valdarnese colpita da meningite.
u' Marted\xec, 25 Maggio 2010 \n Venerd\xc3\x83\xc2\xac 21 Maggio 2010 13:00\n Ufficio Stampa\nL\'igiene pubblica ha gi\xc3\x83\xc2\xa0 provveduto ad avviare la profilassi per le persone che sono state a contatto con lei. Da ieri una signora valdarnese di 64 anni \xc3\x83\xc2\xa8 ricoverata in isolamento nel reparto di malattie infettive del San Donato per una setticemia, con meningite meningococcica di tipo B. La donna \xc3\x83\xc2\xa8 arrivata al Pronto soccorso di Arezzo con febbre alta, stato confusionale e piccoli punti rossi sulla pelle, dovuti ad un sanguinamento sottocutaneo secondario a carenza di piastrine. Segnali inequivocabili della patologia per gli specialisti delle malattie infettive. \xc3\xa2\xc2\x80\xc2\x9cE\' stato importante \xc3\xa2\xc2\x80\xc2\x93 dichiara il direttore della U.O. Malattie infettive Marcello Caremani \xc3\xa2\xc2\x80\xc2\x93 effettuare una diagnosi rapida, perch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa9 con questo tipo di meningite, se non si interviene rapidamente con una adeguata cura antibiotica si possono avere conseguenze gravi. La signora adesso si trova ancora in isolamento, ma gi\xc3\x83\xc2\xa0 stamani le sue condizioni sono migliorate\xc3\xa2\xc2\x80\xc2\x9d. Mentre in ospedale si seguono le condizioni della donna, l\'unit\xc3\x83\xc2\xa0 di Igiene Pubblica della Asl si \xc3\x83\xc2\xa8 mossa sul fronte del controllo e della prevenzione\xc3\x82\xc2\xa0 delle persone che vivono a contatto con la signora, per accertare eventuali pericoli di contagio. La donna, fortunatamente, non ha avuto molti contatti, se non quelli strettamente familiari, per i quali \xc3\x83\xc2\xa8 stata subito avviata la profilassi. Allo stesso tempo, per escludere altre possibilit\xc3\x83\xc2\xa0 di contagio, sono state messe sotto osservazione da parte della Asl e dei rispettivi medici di famiglia, anche amici e conoscenti che in questi giorni sono stati vicini alla signora. Nach Informationen von "osthessen-news" vor Ort und Angaben der Polizei waren in der Rotenburger Jugendherberge zun\xc3\xa4chst 12 Schulkinder und ein Lehrer erkrankt. Sie wurden mit Magen- und Darmbeschwerden sowie Brechreiz von den Rettungsdiensten in Krankenh\xc3\xa4user in Bad Hersfeld und Rotenburg gebracht. Die Ursache der Erkrankungen war zun\xc3\xa4chst unklar: in der Nacht konnten weder Lebensmittelvergiftung, eine Infektion (z.B. Norovirus) oder bakterielle Erkrankung (Salmonellen) ausgeschlossen werden. Mehrere \xc3\x84rzte k\xc3\xbcmmerten sich um die betroffenen Personen und auch das Gesundheitsamt und der Landrat wurden informiert. Bis Mitternacht verschlimmerte sich die Situation - und nun war von 12 jungen Leuten und einem Erwachsenen als Patienten die Rede. Gesprochen wurde von einer "unbekannten Infektion", deren Symptome sich gegen 21.45 Uhr bei den ersten Personen w\xc3\xa4hrend der abendlichen Grillfeier in der Jugendherberge bemerkbar gemacht h\xc3\xa4tten.  ', 'Rotenburg an der Fulda, Hesse, Germany | Norovirus | Humans'

'After ten years of being measles free, Slovenia experienced a cluster with secondary transmission in a hospital setting in March 2010. Steep rise in notified hantavirus infections in Germany, April 2010
'From January to April 2010, 396 hantavirus infections were notified in Germany, a considerable increase compared with previous years (mean: 83 for January-April 2004-2009) including the record-setting year, 2007 (n=232 January-April). Most patients are residents of known Puumala virus endemic areas in southern Germany. The recent increase in notified hantavirus infections is probably due to an increased population density of the main animal reservoir, the bank vole (Myodes glareolus).\n ', 'Germany | Hantavirus | Humans'

'8.215278','126.370277',5,11954
Red Tide Warning - Philippine Information Agency
u'Butuan City (20 May) -- The Bureau of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources (BFAR) of the Department of Agriculture (DA) recently issued an advisory informing the public that Bislig Bay in Surigao del Sur is still positive with red tide toxin, thus shellfish from this area are not safe for human consumption.\n\nBased on the Shellfish Bulletin No.11 Series of 2010 issued by BFAR, the latest laboratory results from their office and the Local Government Units (LGU) revealed that shellfish collected at Dumanquillas Bay in Zamboanga del Sur; Bislig Bay in Bislig City, Surigao del Sur; Matarinao Bay in Eastern Samar; Murclelagos Bay in Zamboanga del Norte and Misamis Occidental; and in the coastal waters of Bolinao and Anda in Pangasinan are still positive for paralytic shellfish poison that is beyond the regulatory limit.\n\nAll types of shellfish and Acetes sp. or alamang gathered from the above banned areas are NOT SAFE for human consumption.\n\nHowever, BFAR said, fish, squids, shrimps, and crabs are safe for human consumption provided that they are fresh and washed thoroughly, and internal organs such as gills and intestines are removed before cooking.\n\nThe list of signs and symptoms for Paralytic shellfish poisoning includes: mild symptoms, facial paresthesia (burning), facial numbness, facial tingling, arm tingling, arm numbness, leg tingling, leg numbness, headache, dizziness, nausea, muscular in coordination and floating sensation. If any of these symptoms are felt, BFAR advised to consult a local physician immediately.\n\nThe following areas continue to be FREE from toxic red tides: coastal waters of Cavite, Pi\xc3\xb1as, Para\xc3\xb1aque, Navotas, Bulacan and Bataan in Manila Bay; coastal waters of Alaminos in Pangasinan; Mansiloc Bay in Zambales; coastal waters of Milagros and Mandaon in Masbate; Inner Malampaya Sound in Taytay and Honda Bay; Juag Lagoon in Matnog and Sorsogon Bay in Sorsogon, all in Luzon.  ', 'Bislig Bay, Surigao del Sur, Philippines | Algae | Humans'

'22.284000','114.150002',5,198
Another report of paralytic shellfish poisoning received - 7thSpace ...
u" \xa0\xa0Another report of paralytic shellfish poisoning received \nHong Kong (HKSAR) - Members of the public are today (May 19) urged to avoid eating fresh scallops for the time being as the Centre for Health Protection (CHP) of the Department of Health has received another report of suspected paralytic shellfish poisoning. A spokesman for CHP said that as at 3pm today, the centre had received a report of two more people falling sick after consuming fresh scallops, bringing to 28 the total number of affected people. They were suspected of having paralytic shellfish poisoning. The two affected patients, a man and a woman from one cluster, were aged 36 and 43.Their main symptoms included limb weakness, dizziness, blurred vision, abdominal pain and nausea which occurred within an hour after consuming scallops at home last Wednesday (May 12).They did not seek medical attention then and both are currently asymptomatic. According to preliminary histories, the fresh scallops were bought from a market in Tai Wai. The case has been referred to the Food and Environmental Hygiene Department for follow up action. Members of the public should seek medical advice immediately if they develop shellfish poisoning symptoms and save any leftovers for investigation and laboratory testing, the spokesman said. The CHP's investigation continues. The spokesman said shellfish poisoning could result from ingestion of bivalve shellfish such as scallops, clams, mussels, oysters and fan shells contaminated with phycotoxins produced by free-living micro-algae, upon which the shellfish feed. Depending on the type of toxin, the clinical symptoms of shellfish poisoning include tingling, numbness, burning of perioral region, diarrhoea, abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting. Severe cases may have difficulty in speaking or breathing. Symptoms usually occur a few minutes to a few hours after consumption of the contaminated shellfish. \nSource: HKSAR Government \nLimited copyright is granted for you to use and/or republish any story on this site for \nany legitimate media purpose as long as you reference 7thSpace and any source mentioned in the story above. Please  ", 'Hong Kong | Poisoning | Humans'

HM Community News Reports
19 May 2010
Dengue
Selangor, Malaysia
'3.509247','101.524803',5,3104
BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'
http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsindex.php?id=499535

BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'

HM Community News Reports
19 May 2010
Chikungunya
Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia
'2.750000','102.166672',5,6832
BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'
http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsindex.php?id=499535

BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'

BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'

BERNAMA - Two Deaths Due To Dengue Within Last Seven Days
'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'

'PUTRAJAYA, May 19 (Bernama) -- A total of 766 dengue cases with two deaths were reported for a period of seven days from May 9, an increase of six cases or one per cent compared with the 760 cases reported in the previous week.\n\nSix states showed a rise in the number of cases reported, namely Selangor (36 cases), Negeri Sembilan (nine cases), Melaka (five), Terengganu (four), Pahang (two) and Penang (one).\n\n"The number of accumulated cases reported for this year was 17,981 cases compared with 20,187 cases for the corresponding period of 2009," said the director-general of health, Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican, in a statement Wednesday.\n\n"Although there is a drop of 11 per cent in the number of cases this year, the number of fatalities also increased by 11 per cent from 52 deaths last year to 58 deaths in the corresponding period of this year," he said.\n\nThe two deaths reported last week were from Selangor, he said.\n\nDr Mohd Ismail said the two deaths, which were due to Dengue Shock Syndrome, occurred in an area where the rate of Aedes breeding was high, which was between two and 3.6 per cent and one of the cases occurred in a dengue hot spot.\n\nMeanwhile, three cases of Chikungunya were reported during the same period, a drop of two cases compared to the five reported in the previous week.\n\nOf the three cases reported, two were in Selangor while the other was in Negeri Sembilan.\n\nThe number of accumulated Chikungunya cases was 549 compared with 1,945 cases, a drop of 1,396 cases or 72 per cent from the corresponding period of 2009.\n ', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Selangor, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Chikungunya | Humans', 'Melaka, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Terengganu, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Pahang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Penang, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans', 'Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia | Dengue | Humans'

4 siblings diagnosed with measles - Omaha.com
' Four siblings now have been diagnosed with measles and are quarantined in Omaha, the Douglas County Health Department said.\n\nThe department announced last week that one member of that family, which doesn\'t live in Nebraska, had been diagnosed with measles. The three additional cases were expected by the department.\n\n"None of the children in the family had been vaccinated," County Health Director Adi Pour said.\n\nDepartment spokesman Phil Rooney said the siblings are Americans who had recently traveled through California, where there is a measles outbreak. He declined to say what state they reside in. ', 'Omaha, Nebraska, United States | Measles | Humans'

Gastroenteritis
Alaska, United States
'64.000198','-150.000305',5,206
Alaska Food Poisoning: May 19, 2010
' # Anchorage, AK. May 17: Undercooked fiddlehead ferns may have been the source of an outbreak of food poisoning that affected at least 20 participants at a Rotary Club luncheon in downtown Anchorage last week. Fiddleheads contain a natural toxin that is inactivated by thorough cooking. The fiddleheads were produced in British Columbia, and sent to a warehouse in California, which then shipped the product to Alaska. FDA is investigating the supply chain. Alaska Food Poisoning: May 19, 2010
' # Anchorage, AK. May 17: Undercooked fiddlehead ferns may have been the source of an outbreak of food poisoning that affected at least 20 participants at a Rotary Club luncheon in downtown Anchorage last week. Fiddleheads contain a natural toxin that is inactivated by thorough cooking. The fiddleheads were produced in British Columbia, and sent to a warehouse in California, which then shipped the product to Alaska. FDA is investigating the supply chain. Norovirus strikes middle school in Port Coquitlam
' Division of Canwest Publishing Inc. \n Nearly 70 Pitt River Middle School students and staff were home sick this week after a suspected case of norovirus spread through the school. \nAbsenteeism surpassed the 20-per-cent mark as a contagious gastrointestinal illness afflicted the school community. Symptoms include vomiting, cramping, chills, fever and diarrhea. "Some students got violently ill quickly with vomiting and of course were sent home," said School District 43 spokesperson Cheryl Quinton. \nThe district sent in extra cleaning crews on Tuesday and Wednesday nights to disinfect high-touch surfaces like doorknobs, tabletops and desktops. \nFraser Health recommends thorough handwashing to prevent the spread of the virus. Lo scorso anno in due mesi, agosto e settembre, la febbre del Nilo infett\xf2 78 persone, morirono in tre, due residenti a Ferrara e una a Mantova. Il virus esploso e tenuto sotto osservazione in Emilia Romagna sta emigrando verso Ovest e ha raggiunto la Lombardia. Un articolo di Eurossurveillance del 22 aprile scorso fa il punto della situazione: le autorit\xe0 sanitarie europee indicano quali sono i territori da tenere sotto controllo. Dal ministero il provvedimento ha raggiunto le Asl: le zone sono quelle comprese fra Mantova, Cremona e Brescia. I serbatoi del virus sono gli uccelli selvatici e le zanzare. La maggior parte delle persone infette non manifesta sintomi, il 20 per cento ha sintomi leggeri: nausea, vomito, linfonodi ingrossati. 'A bat found in a Grayslake church on May 12 has tested positive for rabies, according to the Lake County Health Department.\n\nThe bat was found by a janitor in a bathroom sink of the church. Since the janitor had handled the bat, health department staff advised the janitor to receive rabies post exposure vaccinations.\n\nIt is the second bat that tested positive for rabies in Lake County this year. A bat, found in a Beach Park basement on May 7, was the first bat that tested positive for rabies in the county.\n\nAnyone who has direct contact with a bat or notices a bat acting in an unusual manner, such as flying in daylight or lying on the ground or in your home, should contact the health department at (847) 949-9925. HM Community News Reports
18 May 2010
Dengue
An Giang Province, Vietnam
'10.500000','105.166664',5,10082
Dengue fever grips An Giang Province
"  Dengue fever grips An Giang Province\n\nHealth officials in An Giang have voiced concern over the rapid spread of dengue fever in the province this month. More than 858 cases have been hospitalised with three fatalities since the beginning of May. Most of them were in Long Xuyen City, Cho Moi and Chau Thanh districts.\n\nTu Quoc Tuan, head of the provincial Health Department, warned that the number of dengue cases would increase in coming months. The department asked relevant agencies to spray areas where mosquitoes breed and raise residents' awareness about prevention of dengue and eradication of breeding areas around houses. ", 'An Giang Province, Vietnam | Dengue | Humans'
http://vietnamnews.vnagency.com.vn/Domestic-Press-Highlights/199652/Dengue-fever-grips-An-Giang-Province.html

HM Community News Reports
17 May 2010
Other Plant Disease
Afghanistan
'33.838810','66.026466',5,137
The World Today - Afghan poppy crop hit by mysterious disease ...
"HANE MCLEOD: It's by far Afghanistan's biggest cash crop and it's under threat from a mysterious disease. Opium poppies grown in Afghanistan produces more than 90 per cent of the world's illicit supply of heroin.\n\nThe Taliban uses the profits to finance its operations. Poppy eradication is a key part of NATO's strategy to defeat the insurgents.\n\nBut the effects of the unknown fungal disease are also beginning to affect legal crops and locals suspect NATO is behind the outbreak.\n\nMichael Edwards has this report.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: The heroin that an opium poppy produces might be the scourge of law enforcement agencies in western countries but for farmers in southern Afghanistan the plant represents a vital source of income.\n\nAfghanistan produces 92 per cent of the world's opium but in recent months crop yields have been falling. Farmers says their crops have been hit by a mysterious disease.\n\nFARMER 1 (translated): I don't understand what's happened. It was perfectly okay before but we can see the poppies aren't right when we scratch them to extract the liquid. Before we could cultivate our crops easily. The whole process only took two months.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: Experts says the disease appears to be a fungus which attacks the root of the plant, climbs up the stem and makes the opium capsule wither away. Legal crops and livestock are also being affected.\n\nFARMER 2 (translated): They've sprayed some kind of chemical. They've put it in the water that supplies our crops. People are saying that they've sprayed chemicals but we don't know what they are. I think it's affecting our cattle. They've stopped eating and they're not giving milk. And it's affected our berries and apricots and when we eat them we get sick.\n\nFARMER 3 (translated): I have an apricot farm and it's been affected really badly and I haven't had a good harvest this time.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: The international community has put a massive effort into reducing Afghanistan's opium poppy production.\n\nThe drug provides an income for thousands of poor farmers who are reluctant to switch to legal crops because they are less profitable.\n\nIt also provides a large revenue source for the Taliban. Antonio Maria Costa is the head of the United Nation Office on Drugs and Crime.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: We believe that about half of the opium crops in southern Afghanistan are affected and about half of the total output in these regions will be destroyed which means all together about a quarter of the opium production of last year would be removed from the market because of this infestation.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: Antonio Maria Costa says diseases affecting the opium poppy crop are quite common. But he says he what sets this apart is its severity.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: Opium plants have been affected in Afghanistan. What is new this year is the severity of the problem in the region which is at the heart of the opium cultivation and of course at the heart of the insurgency.\n\nSo it has important political dimension as well as it has important economic dimension for the farmers.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: And Antonio Maria Costa says this political dimension could mean increased support for the Taliban in key areas of southern Afghanistan such as the Helmand Province.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: Certainly farmers that will lose their opium crop and therefore their main source of income will be destabilised in terms of their own social situation and may then be tempted no doubt to ask to be part of the problem of insurgency in Afghanistan.\n\nThen there is a question of the opium economy. The price of opium has already increased in the southern part of the country by over 50 per cent from about $60 a kilo to about $90, $100 a kilo.\n\nAnd third all of these opium price changes will have an impact on the stocks of opium. We have estimated that over the past five years about 10,000 tonnes of unsold opium have been accumulated with a very powerful re-evaluation of these stocks this will have an impact on the funding of insurgency, the funding of terrorists as well as the funding of general organised crime that have been trafficking opium out of Afghanistan.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: NATO has denied it has anything to do with the outbreak.\n\nSHANE MCLEOD: Michael Edwards.  ", 'Afghanistan | Other Plant Disease | Plants', 'Afghanistan | Undiagnosed | Humans'
http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2010/s2899489.htm

The World Today - Afghan poppy crop hit by mysterious disease ...
"HANE MCLEOD: It's by far Afghanistan's biggest cash crop and it's under threat from a mysterious disease. Opium poppies grown in Afghanistan produces more than 90 per cent of the world's illicit supply of heroin.\n\nThe Taliban uses the profits to finance its operations. Poppy eradication is a key part of NATO's strategy to defeat the insurgents.\n\nBut the effects of the unknown fungal disease are also beginning to affect legal crops and locals suspect NATO is behind the outbreak.\n\nMichael Edwards has this report.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: The heroin that an opium poppy produces might be the scourge of law enforcement agencies in western countries but for farmers in southern Afghanistan the plant represents a vital source of income.\n\nAfghanistan produces 92 per cent of the world's opium but in recent months crop yields have been falling. Farmers says their crops have been hit by a mysterious disease.\n\nFARMER 1 (translated): I don't understand what's happened. It was perfectly okay before but we can see the poppies aren't right when we scratch them to extract the liquid. Before we could cultivate our crops easily. The whole process only took two months.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: Experts says the disease appears to be a fungus which attacks the root of the plant, climbs up the stem and makes the opium capsule wither away. Legal crops and livestock are also being affected.\n\nFARMER 2 (translated): They've sprayed some kind of chemical. They've put it in the water that supplies our crops. People are saying that they've sprayed chemicals but we don't know what they are. I think it's affecting our cattle. They've stopped eating and they're not giving milk. And it's affected our berries and apricots and when we eat them we get sick.\n\nFARMER 3 (translated): I have an apricot farm and it's been affected really badly and I haven't had a good harvest this time.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: The international community has put a massive effort into reducing Afghanistan's opium poppy production.\n\nThe drug provides an income for thousands of poor farmers who are reluctant to switch to legal crops because they are less profitable.\n\nIt also provides a large revenue source for the Taliban. Antonio Maria Costa is the head of the United Nation Office on Drugs and Crime.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: We believe that about half of the opium crops in southern Afghanistan are affected and about half of the total output in these regions will be destroyed which means all together about a quarter of the opium production of last year would be removed from the market because of this infestation.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: Antonio Maria Costa says diseases affecting the opium poppy crop are quite common. But he says he what sets this apart is its severity.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: Opium plants have been affected in Afghanistan. What is new this year is the severity of the problem in the region which is at the heart of the opium cultivation and of course at the heart of the insurgency.\n\nSo it has important political dimension as well as it has important economic dimension for the farmers.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: And Antonio Maria Costa says this political dimension could mean increased support for the Taliban in key areas of southern Afghanistan such as the Helmand Province.\n\nANTONIO MARIA COSTA: Certainly farmers that will lose their opium crop and therefore their main source of income will be destabilised in terms of their own social situation and may then be tempted no doubt to ask to be part of the problem of insurgency in Afghanistan.\n\nThen there is a question of the opium economy. The price of opium has already increased in the southern part of the country by over 50 per cent from about $60 a kilo to about $90, $100 a kilo.\n\nAnd third all of these opium price changes will have an impact on the stocks of opium. We have estimated that over the past five years about 10,000 tonnes of unsold opium have been accumulated with a very powerful re-evaluation of these stocks this will have an impact on the funding of insurgency, the funding of terrorists as well as the funding of general organised crime that have been trafficking opium out of Afghanistan.\n\nMICHAEL EDWARDS: NATO has denied it has anything to do with the outbreak.\n\nSHANE MCLEOD: Michael Edwards. Rat plague worsens in Inner Mongolia
' BEIJING - A rat plague is threatening more than 9 million hectares of grasslands in north China\'s Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, local authorities said Monday.\n\nIn recent years, some pastures in Inner Mongolia have been overwhelmed by the burrowing rodents, said Zhang Zhuoran from Department of Agriculture and Animal Husbandry of the region.\n\nThis year\'s persistent drought and grassland degradation are to blame for the rat plague, as rats are more adaptable to dry weather, Zhang said.\n\n"The rats not only eat the grass but also pull out the roots, which increases the region\'s degradation," said Vice Director of Bayan Nur Grassland Station Fan Qiang.\n\nIn recent times, the local government has resorted to spraying poisons with seed machines and airplanes to combat the rats.\n\nAs of Monday, local authorities had mobilized more than 70,000 workers and sprayed over 670 tonnes of poison over 9 million hectares of grassland. City sees unexpected spurt in malaria cases- Hindustan Times
u'Malaria has claimed three lives in the city this month and more that 1,250 people have tested positive for the disease.\n\nDoctors are surprised at the rise in the number of malaria cases, as they usually plummet in summer.\n\nIn April, at least 3,122 Mumbaiites tested positive and two people died of the disease. This is more than double the number of cases in April 2009, which saw 1,351 people diagnosed with malaria. In April 2008, only 790 people contracted the disease.\n\nTransmitted by the bite of infected mosquitoes, a spurt in malaria is normal during the monsoon and post-monsoon period as mosquitoes breed in stagnant water.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWhen temperature crosses 40 deg C, it slows mosquito breeding. But the temperature in Mumbai is lower than that and the humidity level is high, so mosquitoes are continuing to breed,\xe2\x80\x9d said Dr Ashok Bhosale, state project director of the National Vector Borne Disease Control Programme.\n\nThe maximum number of cases has been reported from central Mumbai \xe2\x80\x94 Lower Parel, Worli and Elphinstone Road. On Friday, 21 people who went to KEM Hospital\xe2\x80\x99s Out Patient Department tested positive for malaria. \xe2\x80\x9cI am surprised to see so many malaria cases in the summer. We usually get two to six malaria cases a day,\xe2\x80\x9d said a resident doctor at KEM.\n\nCivic officials believe the rise in construction activity is facilitating mosquito breeding. \xe2\x80\x9cWater stagnates or is left unattended on slabs at the construction sites and it allows for breeding,\xe2\x80\x9d said G.T. Ambe, BMC executive health officer.\n\nThe BMC used to fumigate construction sites but from May 1 the responsibility has been handed over to builders. ', 'Mumbai, Maharashtra, India | Malaria | Humans'

Late blight found in Maryland - baltimoresun.com
" Late blight, the fungus that devastated tomato crops on the East Coast last summer, has been found on tomato plants in Maryland in a St. Mary's County greenhouse.\n\nThe University of Maryland's Extension service has sent representatives to gather plant material and determine whether this is the strain of blight that hit Maryland last year, or a more virulent strain that can winter-over. They will also check to see if the blight has spread beyond the greenhouse where the tomato plants were grown from seed.\n\nJon Traunfeld, head of the Home and Garden Information Center for the Maryland Extension service, said the late blight that hit Maryland last year can only survive on plant material and cannot endure our winter cold. So if gardeners and farmers did a good job of cleaning up their gardens last fall, they should be able to start the season disease-free. Our cold snowy winter, helped, too, he said. New pest damages tomato yield in Turkey
u'FreshPlaza: Global Fresh Produce and Banana News \n New pest damages tomato yield in Turkey \nA tomato pest well-known in Europe and South America, which was found last year in the Dalaman and Fethiye districts of Mu\u011fla, has appeared further along the Mediterranean coast, says an expert. The tuta absoluta pest seriously harms tomatoes and decreases product yield and quality \xc2\x93Tuta absoluta,\xc2\x94 a tomato pest well-known in Europe and South America, has been encountered this year in Antalya, according to a local expert. The pest, which was found last year in the Dalaman and Fethiye districts of the southwestern province of Mu\u011fla, has appeared further along the Mediterranean coast this year, according to Vahap Tuncer, head of the Antalya branch of the Chamber of Agricultural Engineers, or ZMO. \xc2\x93This pest arrived in Turkey via agricultural products imported from Greece last year,\xc2\x94 he said. The tuta absoluta pest, which spreads rapidly, seriously harms tomatoes and decreases product yield and quality, Tuncer said. \xc2\x93To struggle against this pest is difficult as it feeds in the plant\xc2\x92s body and under the leaves. Agricultural pesticides cannot reach the pest, which hides well inside the plant body. To be successful, pesticides should be used during the ovulation period.\xc2\x94 Insufficient measures \nTuta absoluta entered Turkey due to insufficient domestic and foreign quarantine measures, Tuncer said. \xc2\x93This pest came to Turkey via seedlings brought from abroad. The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs should implement measures more effectively. Pesticides to be used in the struggle against pests should be licensed.\xc2\x94 The pest in Antalya province is a new kind, according to Halil Ordu, chairman of the Antalya Chamber of Agriculture. \xc2\x93Nowadays, we are in hot and humid environment. Leaf beetles and fungus reproduce very rapidly due to warm and moist air. We continue our fight against pests under the control of agricultural experts,\xc2\x94 Ordu said. \xc2\x93We are getting acquainted with the pest recently. I assume the ministry\xc2\x92s technical staff is making investigation on this.\xc2\x94 \n Source:  ', 'Antalya Province, Turkey | Pests | Humans'

Animal clinics see increase in fatal dog virus
' Lee County Domestic Animal Services has begun to see more dogs infected with a deadly virus that can be easily prevented with a vaccine.\n\nIn the past month, the Animal Services center has seen three cases of parvovirus, a highly contagious illness spread through contact with fecal matter. Usually, the center goes months without seeing a single parvo case.\n\n"When you see several in a short period of time, you know something\'s going on," said Ria Brown, spokeswoman for the Animal Services center.\n\nPAWS Lee County, a low-cost North Fort Myers animal clinic, also has seen an uptick in parvo cases, taking six calls in one weekend.\n\n"These people had never taken their dog to a vet before," Brown said.\n\nThe virus causes dehydration in dogs, with symptoms such as vomiting and diarrhea. It can be especially severe in puppies, and the virus can remain in soil for up to a year.\n\nDog owners are advised to vaccinate their puppies about once a month in their first 20 weeks, and then once a year. The vaccine usually costs between $15 and $20.\n\nOnce a dog contracts the virus, it\'s often too late.\n\n"I\'ve seen dogs survive it," Brown said. "But more often than not, they\'re\n\nnot going to make it."\n\nIf owners aren\'t getting their pets vaccinated, it could be because of financial reasons, said Suzi Donaldson of Fort Myers, who has a 2-year-old Chihuahua.\n\n"Maybe it\'s due to the tough economy," she said. "Dogs are expensive."\n\nDonaldson has had her dog, Toby, vaccinated.\n\nBen Schanbeck, 61, of North Fort Myers, said people who can\'t afford a vaccine have no business having a dog. Schanbeck\'s 2-year-old pit bull/boxer mix, Gemi, has been vaccinated.\n\n"I think that if you are going to have a dog, you should be able to afford it," he said. "Otherwise, don\'t have a dog." '0.776944','33.957222',5,11910
ReliefWeb \u00bb Document \u00bb Another tragedy in Eastern Uganda, 3 dead
' Another tragedy in Eastern Uganda, 3 dead \nThe Uganda Red Cross Society has distributed essential household items to 660 people camped at Bumatanda Primary School after fleeing their homes in Bubyangu sub county following landslides that ravaged Mbale district.\n According to Kevin Nabutuwa, URCS Regional Programme Officer Disaster Management Mbale Region, the essential household items include 132 jerrycans, 198 bars of soap, 330 plates, 132 mosquito nets, 132 saucepans, 198 blankets and 330 cups have been handed out to the people.\n A detailed assessment is being carried out by URCS along side the distribution of the essential household items. Three children were killed by the landslides which have displaced over 400 people and destroyed gardens. The dead whose bodies were recovered about two kilometers away from their homes were Amina Nandutu 13, Juma Kyikumi 10 and Namusilo Manisula 6. Nine villages were affected and these are Upper and Lower Bukwana, Upper and Lower Bunabuloli, Bunadudu, Gumu, Bukwaga, Kitumba and Lusamente.\n The tragedy took place on 15th May 2010 when torrential rains that lasted three hours from 10:00pm to 1:00am swept through the villages carrying along mud and big stones down the slopes of the hilly area. Nabutuwa further said that an additional 150 households are at risk of being swept away by the landslides. ', 'Kirewa, Uganda | Cholera | Humans', 'Kirewa, Uganda | Environmental | Humans'

Genova &#8211; Meningite dopo operazione al San Martino
u' Comunicati Stampa e Comunicazioni \nGenova \u2013 Contrae la meningite durante una operazione all\u2019ospedale San Martino. Un giovane di 33 anni, residente a Quarto, \xc3\xa8 ricoverato in gravi condizioni nel nosocomio genovese a seguito di una forte infezione da meningococco, il batterio che sviluppa la meningite. \nL\u2019uomo si era sottoposto ad un intervento chirurgico \u201cdi routine\u201d per la rimozione di alcuni polipi presenti nella mucosa nasale. Qualcosa, per\xc3\xb2, \xc3\xa8 andata storta e qualche giorno dopo l\u2019operazione ha iniziato a stare male, con febbre alta, nausea e fortissimi mal di testa. \nUna visita in ospedale ha chiarito il mistero. Il suo \xc3\xa8 un caso di infezione batterica ospedaliera e ingrossa il gi\xc3\xa0 preoccupante elenco dei casi che si registrano ogni anno in Italia. Pazienti che si infettano in ospedale dove ci si aspetterebbe ambienti sani e disinfettati e dove, invece, si annidano batteri anche molto insidiosi e resistenti persino agli antibiotici. \nSul caso \xc3\xa8 stata aperta una indagine interna da parte dell\u2019ospedale San Martino.  ', 'Genoa, Liguria, Italy | Bacterial Meningitis | Humans'
