'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Rift Valley Fever in South Africa - Update No 2
u' Las rickettsias son bacterias que pueden causar muchas enfermedades que se transmiten por artr\xf3podos hemat\xf3fagos como las pulgas, piojos o garrapatas. Entre las manifestaciones de las rickettsiosis se encuentran las erupciones cut\xe1neas, la fiebre y los s\xedntomas gripales. La fiebre por picadura de garrapata africana, causada por Rickettsia africae, es generalmente leve, con erupci\xf3n cut\xe1nea menor y escasa tendencia a presentar complicaciones. Todas las rickettsiosis responden al tratamiento con antibi\xf3ticos como la doxiciclina o la tetraciclina. Hasta el 10 de mayo el Gobierno de Sud\xe1frica hab\xeda notificado 186 casos humanos confirmados de FVR, 18 de ellos mortales, en las provincias de Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape y North West. La FVR es una enfermedad v\xedrica que afecta principalmente a los animales (ganado vacuno, b\xfafalos, ovejas, cabras y camellos), pero tambi\xe9n puede afectar al ser humano. El principal modo de transmisi\xf3n de la FVR es el contacto directo o indirecto con sangre u \xf3rganos de animales infectados. Tambi\xe9n ha habido casos humanos por picadura de mosquitos infectados, y hay pruebas de que el ser humano se puede infectar mediante la ingesti\xf3n de leche no pasteurizada o no hervida de animales infectados. La OMS no aconseja restricciones a los viajes internacionales con origen o destino a Sud\xe1frica, pero recomienda que quienes viajen a ese pa\xeds, y en especial quienes tengan previsto visitar granjas o reservas de caza, eviten el contacto con sangre y tejidos animales, as\xed como la ingesti\xf3n de leche no pasteurizada o no hervida y de carne cruda.  Los viajeros deben tomar precauciones adecuadas contras las picaduras de mosquitos y otros insectos hemat\xf3fagos (uso de repelentes, camisas de manga larga, pantalones largos y mosquiteros). Los profesionales y los servicios de medicina de los viajeros deben conocer la situaci\xf3n actual de la FVR en Sud\xe1frica para prestar los consejos y la atenci\xf3n pertinentes.  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rickettsia | Humans', 'Germany | Rickettsia | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_12/es/index.html

'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Rift Valley Fever in South Africa - update
u' Hasta el 3 de mayo de 2010, el Ministerio de Salud de Sud\xe1frica hab\xeda notificado 172 casos, 15 de ellos mortales, desde el inicio del brote en las provincias de Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape y North West. Aunque la mayor\xeda de los casos refieren haber tenido contacto directo con ganado infectado por el virus de la FVR o est\xe1n epidemiol\xf3gicamente relacionados con granjas en las que ha habido casos confirmados de FVR en los animales, en algunos todav\xeda no se conoce la v\xeda de transmisi\xf3n, y no se puede excluir la exposici\xf3n a mosquitos infectados.  El Gobierno de Sud\xe1frica ha aplicado medidas de salud p\xfablica para controlar el brote: difusi\xf3n entre la poblaci\xf3n de mensajes fundamentales para reducir el riesgo, elaboraci\xf3n de directrices para el personal sanitario sobre la identificaci\xf3n y notificaci\xf3n de los casos, la investigaci\xf3n de laboratorio, el manejo cl\xednico de los casos, el control de las infecciones hospitalarias, las medidas de salud p\xfablica para la prevenci\xf3n y el control, y la vacunaci\xf3n de los animales en las zonas no afectadas. La OMS no aconseja restricciones a los viajes internacionales con origen o destino a Sud\xe1frica, pero recomienda que quienes viajen a ese pa\xeds, y en especial quienes tengan previsto visitar granjas o reservas de caza, eviten el contacto con sangre y tejidos animales, as\xed como la ingesti\xf3n de leche no pasteurizada o no hervida y de carne cruda.  Los viajeros deben tomar precauciones adecuadas contras las picaduras de mosquitos y otros insectos hemat\xf3fagos (uso de repelentes y mosquiteros). Los profesionales y los servicios de medicina de los viajeros deben conocer la situaci\xf3n actual de la FVR en Sud\xe1frica para prestar los consejos y la atenci\xf3n pertinentes.  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Germany | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_04a/es/index.html

Organisation mondiale de la Sant\u00e9

Rickettsia

'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Valley Fever Rift in South Africa - update 2
u' Les rickettsies sont des bact\xe9ries pouvant entra\xeener de nombreuses maladies et elles se transmettent par des arthropodes parasites h\xe9matophages, comme les puces, les poux ou les tiques. Les sympt\xf4mes des rickettsioses comportent une \xe9ruption cutan\xe9e, de la fi\xe8vre et des sympt\xf4mes d\u2019allure grippale. La fi\xe8vre \xe0 tiques africaine est caus\xe9e par Rickettsia africae. Elle tend \xe0 \xeatre moins grave, avec un exanth\xe8me moins important, et \xe9volue rarement vers des complications. Toutes les rickettsioses r\xe9agissent au traitement par des antibiotiques, comme la doxycycline ou la t\xe9tracycline. Au 10 mai 2010, le Minist\xe8re de la Sant\xe9 d\u2019Afrique du Sud avait notifi\xe9 186 cas confirm\xe9s de FVR chez l\u2019homme, dont 18 mortels, dans les provinces de l\u2019\xc9tat-Libre, du Cap-Oriental, du Cap-du-Nord, du Cap-Occidental et du Nord-Ouest. La FVR est une infection virale affectant principalement les animaux (bovins, buffles, ch\xe8vres, moutons et chameaux), mais elle peut \xe9galement toucher l\u2019\xeatre humain. Son principal mode de transmission est par contact direct ou indirect avec du sang ou des organes d\u2019animaux infect\xe9s. On a \xe9galement observ\xe9 chez l\u2019\xeatre humain des infections r\xe9sultant de la piq\xfbre de moustiques infect\xe9s. Selon certaines donn\xe9es, l\u2019\xeatre humain pourrait s\u2019infecter en consommant du lait cr\xfb ou non pasteuris\xe9 provenant d\u2019animaux atteints.  L\u2019OMS ne pr\xe9conise aucune restriction aux voyages \xe0 destination ou en provenance d\u2019Afrique du Sud. En revanche, elle recommande aux visiteurs se rendant dans ce pays, notamment ceux qui ont l\u2019intention d\u2019aller dans des exploitations agricoles ou des r\xe9serves naturelles, d\u2019\xe9viter tout contact avec des tissus ou du sang des animaux, de ne pas boire de lait cr\xfb ou non pasteuris\xe9 et de ne pas manger de viande crue.  Tous les voyageurs doivent prendre les mesures n\xe9cessaires pour se prot\xe9ger des piq\xfbres de moustiques et autres insectes h\xe9matophages (s\u2019enduire de produits r\xe9pulsifs, porter des chemises \xe0 manches longues et des pantalons longs, dormir sous une moustiquaire). Les professionnels et les services de la m\xe9decine des voyages doivent avoir connaissance de la situation actuelle de la FVR en Afrique du Sud, afin de prodiguer des soins et des conseils en cons\xe9quence.  ', 'South Africa | Rickettsia | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_12/fr/index.html

HM Community News Reports
13 May 2010
White nose syndrome
Missouri, United States
'38.238098','-92.504898',5,227
Group warns of mysterious bat plague sweeping country \u2013 This Just In ...
u"Wildlife agencies in all 48 of the contiguous U.S. states have been put on notice after a mysterious bat-killing disease \xe2\x80\x93 white nose syndrome \xe2\x80\x93 was recently detected west of the Mississippi River.\n\nThe fungal disease, which has a 100 percent fatality rate, was first discovered in bats four years ago in Albany, New York, said Mollie Matteson, conservation advocate for the Center for Biological Diversity.\n\nThe disease has subsequently spread into the Midwest, parts of the South, Canada, and most recently, Missouri, Matteson said.\n\nLetters were sent to wildlife agencies to spur agencies to come up with response plans to stop the disease that has baffled scientists, Matteson said.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cIt's absolutely devastating for the species it has affected so far,\xe2\x80\x9d Matteson said. The disease seems to strike only bats that hibernate, Matteson said.\n\nWRTV: Bat disease keeping many Indiana caves closed\n\nThe disease, typically manifested by a white coat on the nose and in some cases on the animal's fur, has affected six species of the approximately 45 bat species in the entire United States.\n\nBut humans should be concerned.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWhile we haven\xe2\x80\x99t heard anything about transmission to humans, people can spread the disease,\xe2\x80\x9d Matteson said.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cThey can spread it on their clothing and gear, because the fungal spores can be in the caves, particularly if people are crawling on the ground,\xe2\x80\x9d she said. \xe2\x80\x9cIf they leave one cave where the spores are and go into another, they can contaminate it with those spores,\xe2\x80\x9d causing an outbreak, Matteson said.\n\nA nonfatal version of the disease has been found in bats in Europe, Matteson said, but \xe2\x80\x9cbats here in North America have no defense.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\nAlthough scientists are experimenting with various anti-fungal treatments, there is no known cure or effective treatment for white nose syndrome, Matteson said.\nPost by: Journalist Craig Johnson\nFiled under: Animals \xe2\x80\xa2 Environment \xe2\x80\xa2 Latest news\n ", 'Missouri, United States | White nose syndrome | Bats'

['<img class=\\"f\\" src=\\"..\\/w\\" title=\\"World Health Organization\\" alt=\\"World Health Organization\\" \\/>', '12 May 2010', '<a href=\\"..\\/ai.php?426247&trto=en&trfr=en&pid179\\" class=\\"fbox\\">Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2<\\/a>', 'Rift Valley Fever', '<a href=\\"javascript:sc(\'-28.998529\',\'25.092541\',5,179);\\">South Africa<\\/a>', 'Humans', '186', '18']
3
426247

World Health Organization
12 May 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2
' Rickettsia, commonly known as tick fever is a bacterium which can cause many diseases that are transmitted by blood-sucking parasitic arthropods such as fleas, lice and ticks. Symptoms of rickettsial infections include rash, fever, and flulike symptoms. African tick bite fever is caused by rickettsia africae and tends to be a milder illness, with less prominent rash and little tendency to progress to complicated disease. All rickettsial diseases respond to treatment with antibiotics such as doxycycline and tetracycline  As of 10 May, the Government of South Africa has reported 186 confirmed cases of RVF in humans, including 18 deaths, in Free State Province, Eastern Cape Province, Northern Cape Province, Western Cape, and North West Province. RVF is a viral disease that primarily affects animals (such as cattle, buffalo, sheep, goats and camels). The disease can also affect humans. The main mode of transmission of RVF is via direct or indirect contact with the blood or organs of infected animals. Human infections have also resulted from the bites of infected mosquitoes. There is evidence that humans may become infected by ingesting the unpasteurized or uncooked milk of infected animals. WHO advises no international travel restriction to or from South Africa. However, WHO recommends that visitors to South Africa, especially those intending to visit farms and/or game reserves, avoid coming into contact with animal tissues or blood, avoid drinking unpasteurized or uncooked milk or eating raw meat.  All travelers should take appropriate precautions against bites from mosquitoes and other blood-sucking insects (including the use of insect repellents, wearing long-sleeved shirts and trousers, and sleeping under mosquito nets). Travel medicine professionals and travel medicine services should be aware of the current RVF situation in South Africa in order to provide advice and care accordingly.  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rickettsia | Humans', 'Germany | Rickettsia | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_12/en/index.html
Humans

Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2
' Rickettsia, commonly known as tick fever is a bacterium which can cause many diseases that are transmitted by blood-sucking parasitic arthropods such as fleas, lice and ticks. Symptoms of rickettsial infections include rash, fever, and flulike symptoms. African tick bite fever is caused by rickettsia africae and tends to be a milder illness, with less prominent rash and little tendency to progress to complicated disease. All rickettsial diseases respond to treatment with antibiotics such as doxycycline and tetracycline  As of 10 May, the Government of South Africa has reported 186 confirmed cases of RVF in humans, including 18 deaths, in Free State Province, Eastern Cape Province, Northern Cape Province, Western Cape, and North West Province. RVF is a viral disease that primarily affects animals (such as cattle, buffalo, sheep, goats and camels). The disease can also affect humans. The main mode of transmission of RVF is via direct or indirect contact with the blood or organs of infected animals. Human infections have also resulted from the bites of infected mosquitoes. There is evidence that humans may become infected by ingesting the unpasteurized or uncooked milk of infected animals. WHO advises no international travel restriction to or from South Africa. However, WHO recommends that visitors to South Africa, especially those intending to visit farms and/or game reserves, avoid coming into contact with animal tissues or blood, avoid drinking unpasteurized or uncooked milk or eating raw meat.  All travelers should take appropriate precautions against bites from mosquitoes and other blood-sucking insects (including the use of insect repellents, wearing long-sleeved shirts and trousers, and sleeping under mosquito nets). Travel medicine professionals and travel medicine services should be aware of the current RVF situation in South Africa in order to provide advice and care accordingly.  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rickettsia | Humans', 'Germany | Rickettsia | Humans'

'51.106560','10.393650',5,101
Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update 2
' Rickettsia, commonly known as tick fever is a bacterium which can cause many diseases that are transmitted by blood-sucking parasitic arthropods such as fleas, lice and ticks. Symptoms of rickettsial infections include rash, fever, and flulike symptoms. African tick bite fever is caused by rickettsia africae and tends to be a milder illness, with less prominent rash and little tendency to progress to complicated disease. All rickettsial diseases respond to treatment with antibiotics such as doxycycline and tetracycline  As of 10 May, the Government of South Africa has reported 186 confirmed cases of RVF in humans, including 18 deaths, in Free State Province, Eastern Cape Province, Northern Cape Province, Western Cape, and North West Province. RVF is a viral disease that primarily affects animals (such as cattle, buffalo, sheep, goats and camels). The disease can also affect humans. The main mode of transmission of RVF is via direct or indirect contact with the blood or organs of infected animals. Human infections have also resulted from the bites of infected mosquitoes. There is evidence that humans may become infected by ingesting the unpasteurized or uncooked milk of infected animals. WHO advises no international travel restriction to or from South Africa. However, WHO recommends that visitors to South Africa, especially those intending to visit farms and/or game reserves, avoid coming into contact with animal tissues or blood, avoid drinking unpasteurized or uncooked milk or eating raw meat.  All travelers should take appropriate precautions against bites from mosquitoes and other blood-sucking insects (including the use of insect repellents, wearing long-sleeved shirts and trousers, and sleeping under mosquito nets). Travel medicine professionals and travel medicine services should be aware of the current RVF situation in South Africa in order to provide advice and care accordingly.  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rickettsia | Humans', 'Germany | Rickettsia | Humans'

Two raccoons rabid in Chautauqua County | WIVB.com
" Two raccoons rabid in Chautauqua County \n Updated: Tuesday, 11 May 2010, 8:48 PM EDT Published : Tuesday, 11 May 2010, 8:48 PM EDT \n MAYVILLE, N.Y. (RELEASE) - The Chautauqua County Department of Health recently submitted two raccoon specimens from opposite ends of the County to the NYS Wadsworth Laboratory in Albany for rabies testing. The Health Department received notification on May 11 that the animals have been confirmed as positive for rabies. \nOn May 7, an unprovoked raccoon bit a 19-year old male in Falconer and then fled. It is believed that the same raccoon then attacked a dog outside a residence and another man by biting through his pant leg. The man was able to kill the raccoon by strangulation. Fortunately, neither men nor dog were seriously injured but because the two men had direct contact with the rabies virus through saliva of the raccoon. Robert Berke, M.D., County Medical Director, authorized post-exposure rabies prophylaxis to prevent the development of rabies. The dog had a current rabies vaccination and therefore, only required a booster. \nOn May 5, a raccoon attacked a dog in the Town of Sheridan. Unfortunately, the dog's rabies vaccination was outdated and after re-vaccination, the dog will need to be quarantined for a six month period for observation. Fortunately, no human contact was made with the raccoon's saliva.  ", 'Chautauqua County, New York, United States | Rabies | Humans'

Highland Lakes Newspapers - Two rabies cases confirmed in Rio Llano ...
u" Subscribe to Online or Print Editions \n Official Information \n The Llano County Sheriff's Office and Texas Department of State Health Services Laboratory confirmed two animals that recently died near the city of Llano were infected with rabies. Authorities said Thursday that both a black cat, which died Monday on Rio Llano Drive West, and a raccoon, which was killed by a rancher\xe2\x80\x99s dog on Sunday on CR 201B, were infected with rabies. Rio Llano Drive West is located in the Rio Llano subdivision just west of the city of Llano on SH 29, and CR 201B is located a few miles east of the city on SH 29. There has been one other rabies case so far this year involving a skunk in Babyhead in March. Janie Crumpler, animal control officer for the Llano County Sheriff\xe2\x80\x99s Office, said the two recent cases put the county ahead of the total number of rabies cases for all of last year. For more information, contact either the Llano County Animal Control at 325.247.5767 or the Texas Department of State Health Services Zoonosis Control Program at 254.778.6744. Louisiana Hospital Food Poisoning Cases Linked to Chicken Salad - ...
'Investigators say that chicken salad contaminated with norovirus is the most likely source for a hospital food poisoning outbreak that has killed three and sickened 44 in total at Central State Hospital in Louisiana. \n\nThe Louisiana hospital food poisoning cases were first noticed when patients began showing signs of gastrointestinal distress on Friday morning. Between late Friday night and early Saturday morning a 41-year-old man, a 52-year-old man and a 43-year-old woman died due to food poisoning complications at the mental health hospital; which is located in Pineville, between Shreveport and Baton Rouge.\n\nIn all, 40 patients and 4 staff members have fallen ill. Fifteen of those victims, including all four sick staff members, were taken to Huey P. Long Medical Center in Pineville for treatment. At least two remained hospitalized through Saturday.\n\nAll of the patients who contracted food poisoning had eaten chicken salad on Thursday night. State health department officials said that there could have been something wrong with the chicken, lettuce or mayonnaise. Some officials have said that the chief suspect is norovirus, which can cause gastroenteritis, but that has not been confirmed. Autopsies to be performed on the three deceased patients could provide investigators with more information. ', 'Central Louisiana State Hospital, Louisiana, United States | Gastroenteritis | Humans'

AfricaNews - Measles attacks 3,026, kills 8 in Malawi - The ...
' Mtheto Lungu, AfricaNews reporter in Lilongwe, Malawi \n Outbreak of measles in Malawi had taken ill over 3,000 people and killed eight in Blantyre alone. Twenty-six cases have been recorded by Monday in Mwanza and Neno districts. Health officials had last week announced it would require $4.1 million to vaccinate over six million children countrywide. \n The situation has forced the government to jump the gun and implement its three year interval measles civic education and vaccination campaign to kick start immediately. Four districts in Malawi\'s Southern region, including Blantyre, are now on the crash programme. \r\nLast week campaigns were rolled out in Blantyre, Chiradzulu and Mzimba districts. \r\nDeputy Minister of Health Theresa Mwale said: "With assistance from MSF, France and Belgium we have rolled out this vaccination campaign. Dr. Andrea Bengel-Flach, Medizinische Leiterin des Gesundheitsamts Ortenaukreis, empfiehlt daher allen B\xc3\xbcrgerinnen und B\xc3\xbcrgern, ihren Impfschutz gegen Masern zu pr\xc3\xbcfen. Eltern sollten den Masernimpfschutz ihrer Kinder und Jugendlichen kontrollieren. \nMasern geh\xc3\xb6ren zu den Viruserkrankungen, gegen die es keine urs\xc3\xa4chliche Behandlung gibt. Die Erreger werden nur von Mensch zu Mensch durch Tr\xc3\xb6pfcheninfektion \xc3\xbcbertragen. Die Ansteckungsf\xc3\xa4higkeit beginnt bereits f\xc3\xbcnf Tage vor und h\xc3\xa4lt bis vier Tage nach Auftreten des maserntypischen Hautausschlags an. Von der Ansteckung bis zum Erscheinen des Ausschlags vergehen etwa 14 Tage. Die Erkrankung beginnt oft mit hohem Fieber, Husten, Schnupfen und Bindehautentz\xc3\xbcndung. Nach drei bis vier Tagen tritt unter erneutem Fieberanstieg der f\xc3\xbcr die Krankheit typische, fleckige Ausschlag am Kopf und dem gesamten K\xc3\xb6rper auf. Bei zehn bis 20 Prozent der Erkrankten kommt es zu Komplikationen wie Mittelohrentz\xc3\xbcndung, Lungenentz\xc3\xbcndung und Gehirnentz\xc3\xbcndung. HM Community News Reports
6 May 2010
Bluetongue
United Kingdom
'54.470001','-2.021500',5,40
UK - Bluetongue in cattle
' 07 May 2010 \n National veterinary associations are warning livestock farmers that a major Bluetongue virus (BTV8) threat still exists due to the extremely high numbers of animals being imported to Britain from the confluent Protection Zone in mainland Europe this year. \n The British Veterinary Association (BVA) and its specialist divisions the British Cattle Veterinary Association (BCVA), Sheep Veterinary Society (SVS) and Goat Veterinary Society (GVS) are calling on farmers to vaccinate and revaccinate their stock and to make a very careful risk assessment of the need to import animals. \n The latest import figures from Animal Health reveal that in the first quarter of 2010 (Jan-Mar) nearly 5000 animals were imported to Britain. This is more than in the whole of 2008 (4,000 animals imported) and, if this rate continues, we could see a 50% increase in imports on 2009 (13,000 animals imported). \nThe Bluetongue Experts Group (consisting of scientists from the Institute of Animal Health, Met Office, Defra vets and epidemiologists and representatives from the Devolved Administrations) has looked at the two main routes for disease to re-enter Britain, ie via wind-borne midge incursion from Continental Europe or via an animal movement into the country. Based on information regarding the disease situation in the EU and data on imported animals, the group concluded that importation is a greater risk than wind-borne spread not only for BTV8 but also for other strains such as BTV 1 that is still present on mainland Europe.  ', 'United Kingdom | Bluetongue | Humans'
http://www.meattradenewsdaily.co.uk/news/110510/uk___bletongue_in_cattle.aspx

Infection with Mayaro virus in a French traveller returning from ...
'Mayaro virus (MAYV) disease is a mosquito-borne zoonosis endemic in humid forests of tropical South America. MAYV is closely related to other alphaviruses that produce a dengue-like illness accompanied by long-lasting arthralgia. A French tourist developed high-grade fever and severe joint manifestations following a 15-day trip in the Amazon basin, Brazil, and was diagnosed with MAYV infection in January 2010. This case is the first reported in a traveller returning from an endemic South American country to Europe. ', 'Brazil | Not Yet Classified | Humans', 'France | Not Yet Classified | Humans'

u' Calvary Day School student tests positive for Tuberculosis \n The Chatham County Health Department has confirmed that a 12th grade student at Calvary Day School has tested positive for tuberculosis (TB). \nAccording to a release issued by the Health Department, an investigation into the possible exposure is under way, and the Health Department will identify those students and staff who may require testing. \xe2\x80\x9cWe are working with school officials to screen those who may have been in contact with the student while he was contagious,\xe2\x80\x9d said Dr. Diane Weems, Chief Medical Officer for the Chatham County Health Department and Coastal Health District. \xe2\x80\x9cIt is important to note that if someone tests positive for TB, it simply means that at some point they have been exposed to the disease but it does not necessarily mean that they have active TB.\xe2\x80\x9d \nAbout tuberculosis (TB) \nTB is a disease caused by germs that are spread from person to person through the air and often affects the lungs. TB is spread when a person inhales airborne germs over a prolonged period of time in a confined area from someone with the disease who coughs or sneezes. In addition to the lungs, TB can also affect other parts of the body. \xa0  ', 'Calvary Day School, Savannah, Georgia, USA | Tuberculosis | Humans'

5 May 2010
Whooping Cough
Kern County, California, United States
'35.296070','-118.667595',5,8743
Whooping Cough Impacting Locals - Bakersfield News Story - KERO ...
' BAKERSFIELD, Calif. -- Parents beware. What seems like a simple cough can kill your child. Pertussis, commonly known as whooping cough, is a highly contagious bacterial infection that attacks the respiratory system. Initial symptoms are runny nose, sneezing and mild cough that eventually develops into coughing spells lasting up to a minute.\n\n"Children who have narrow airways will get edema in the airways and when they cough they whoop," said Dr. Royce Johnson of Kern Medical Center.\n\nJohnson said if left untreated, whooping cough can kill your baby. The Public Health Department says the last peak in whooping cough was 2005 when California reported 3,100 cases. It\'s due for a comeback this year and is already hitting the Central Valley hard with 3 to 4 times as many cases this year compared to last year. So far this year, Kern County has 20 cases compared to six cases last year. ', 'Kern County, California, United States | Whooping Cough | Humans'

Organisation mondiale de la Sant\u00e9
4 May 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Fever Rift Valley: the situation in South Africa
u' Au 3 mai 2010, le Minist\xe8re de la Sant\xe9 d\u2019Afrique du Sud avait notifi\xe9 172 cas, dont 15 mortels, depuis le d\xe9but de la flamb\xe9e dans les provinces de l\u2019\xc9tat-Libre, du Cap-Oriental, du Cap-du-Nord, du Cap-Occidental et du Nord-Ouest. M\xeame si l\u2019on signale que la plupart de ces cas ont eu des contacts directs avec du cheptel infect\xe9 par la FVR et/ou des liens \xe9pid\xe9miologiques avec des \xe9levages ayant des cas confirm\xe9s de FVR chez l\u2019animal, on ignore toujours la voie de transmission pour un certain nombre de cas. Pour ces derniers, il est impossible d\u2019exclure la possibilit\xe9 d\u2019une exposition par des moustiques infect\xe9s.  Les autorit\xe9s sud-africaines ont pris des mesures de sant\xe9 publique, comportant la mise au point, \xe0 l\u2019intention de la population expos\xe9e, de messages essentiels pour la r\xe9duction des risques et, \xe0 l\u2019intention des professionnels de sant\xe9, des directives pour l\u2019identification et la notification des cas, les analyses de laboratoires, la prise en charge clinique des cas, les mesures de lutte contre l\u2019infection dans les h\xf4pitaux. Elles ont aussi pr\xe9vu des mesures de pr\xe9vention et de lutte, ainsi que la vaccination des animaux, dans les zones non touch\xe9es.  L\u2019OMS ne pr\xe9conise aucune restriction aux voyages \xe0 destination ou en provenance d\u2019Afrique du Sud. En revanche, elle recommande aux visiteurs se rendant dans ce pays, notamment ceux qui ont l\u2019intention d\u2019aller dans des exploitations agricoles ou des r\xe9serves naturelles, d\u2019\xe9viter tout contact avec des tissus ou du sang des animaux, de ne pas boire de lait cr\xfb ou non pasteuris\xe9 et de ne pas manger de viande crue. Tous les voyageurs doivent prendre les mesures n\xe9cessaires pour se prot\xe9ger des piq\xfbres de moustiques (moustiquaires, produits r\xe9pulsifs). Les professionnels et les services de la m\xe9decine des voyages doivent avoir connaissance de la situation actuelle de la FVR en Afrique du Sud, afin de prodiguer des soins et des conseils en cons\xe9quence.Pour en savoir plus Minist\xe8re de la Sant\xe9 d\u2019Afrique du Sud    The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)   Robert Koch Institute   Rift Valley fever: WHO fact sheet - en anglais   Protection antivectorielle [pdf 548kb] [pdf 548kb]International Travel and Health  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Germany | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_04a/fr/index.html

Hong Kong: CHP investigates rotavirus gastroenteritis outbreak in ...
'The Centre for Health Protection (CHP) of the Department of Health today (May 5) reminded the public and management of institutions to maintain strict personal, food and environmental hygiene to prevent gastroenteritis.\n\nThe appeal followed the CHPs investigation into a gastroenteritis outbreak affecting 18 children aged between three and five and two staff members in a kindergarten in Fanling.\n\nThe affected, comprising seven males and 13 females, have developed symptoms of gastroenteritis including diarrhoea, vomiting, fever and abdominal pain since April 24. One of the children required hospitalisation and had been discharged. All the affected are currently in stable condition.\n\nThe stool samples of one affected child tested positive for rotavirus.\n\nOfficers of the CHP have visited the institution and provided health advice to staff concerning proper disinfection, disposal of vomitus and faecal matter, as well as personal and food hygiene.\n\nTo prevent the spread of viral gastroenteritis, the public should take the following precautions:\n\n* wash hands thoroughly before handling food and eating and after using the toilet or handling vomitus or faecal matter;\n* wear gloves when disposing of vomitus or faeces, and wash hands afterwards;\n* clean and disinfect contaminated areas or items promptly and thoroughly with household bleach diluted at a ratio of 1:50 (by adding one part household bleach to 49 parts water);\n* maintain good indoor ventilation;\n* make sure that food, particularly seafood and shellfish, is cooked thoroughly. ', 'Fanling, Hong Kong | Gastroenteritis | Humans'

HM Community News Reports
5 May 2010
Chikungunya
Hole Narsipur, Karnataka, India
'12.784140','76.244438',5,11722
More than 300 hit by Chikungunya
" Hassan: The growing menace of Chikungunya has hit more than 300 people and has claimed one person's life in Annechakanahalli in Holenarsipur taluk of Hassan district. The deceased has been identified as Rangaiah (55). But sadly, the taluk health officer claims that he is unaware of the prevalent situation. \nThe officer, Dr. Rajesh said that though the menace began almost a month ago, he was not aware of the attacks in the village. While clarifying that he yet hasn't received any complaint with this regard, he notified that he got to know about this only on Friday and he had directed Dr. Sidde Gowda to visit the village on Saturday. However, Dr. Sidde Gowda said he had treated all the cases. \n The village comes under the Doddakadanuru Primary Health Centre (PHC). The inhabitants of the village stated that they had visited Doddakannuru PHC sometime ago, to report the symptoms of Chikungunya, but the medical officer didn't respond to them in a proper manner. Now, the disease has engulfed the whole village, just within a month. \nThey grumbled that they were asked to pay Rs 80/- for a glucose saline and Rs. 2/- for a needle at the PHC. They have demanded action against the officers. The people of the village informed that there was an overhead tank in the village which had not been cleaned and that they were receiving contaminated water. \nRamakrishne Gowda, a resident, said chikungunya has affected him and three others in his family. He said that the doctors did not bother to visit the village even after they were informed about the death of Rangaiah a week ago, due to Chikungunya. Malle Gowda said that in his house three persons were down with chikungunya. Another villager, Shantaraju, said that since one month, he was taking several people from the village to the Doddakadanuru PHC for treatment.  ", 'Hole Narsipur, Karnataka, India | Chikungunya | Humans'

u' Al 4 doden aan Q-koorts in 2010 \n Het aantal sterfgevallen aan Q-koorts is in 2010 opgelopen tot 4. Het aantal meldingen van Q-koorts bedraagt nu 274. Hiervan hadden 160 pati\xc3\xabnten hun eerste ziektedag in 2010. \nDat blijkt uit de nieuwste cijfers van het Rijksinstituut voor Volksgezondheid en Milieu (RIVM). Van 88 pati\xc3\xabnten is bekend dat zij in 2009 ziek zijn geworden, 6 pati\xc3\xabnten maakten hun eerste ziektedag in de jaren daarvoor door. Ook hadden de zij al een medisch verleden. \nAls in het laboratorium een Q-koorts besmetting is vastgesteld, wordt dit doorgegeven aan de GGD. Whooping cough on the rise in Fresno | Vaccine News Daily
" Whooping Cough On The Rise In Fresno \n Whooping cough on the rise in Fresno \n The number of whooping cough cases in Fresno, California, is on the rise, health officials have said, adding that a Fresno County infant died from the disease recently. \nThirty-five cases of whooping cough have already be reported this year, the Fresno County Health Department confirmed. HM Community News Reports
4 May 2010
Diarrhea
Kathmandu, Central Region, Nepal
'27.716667','85.316666',5,2877
Fear of epidemic in Kathmandu as Maoist strike enters third day
u'Kathmandu, May 4 (IANS) The fear of a diarrhoea and dysentery epidemic - that last year killed hundreds of people - began to grow in capital city Kathmandu as the indefinite general strike called by the opposition Maoist party reached the third consecutive day Tuesday with neither the former guerrillas nor the ruling parties showing any signs of relenting.\nDozens of Maoist protesters, who fell ill due to contaminated drinking water, food and unsafe sanitation while camping on the streets and open spaces of the capital, had to be admitted to various hospitals while outbreaks were also reported in outer districts like Dang in western Nepal.\n\nSince May 2, after Prime Minister Madhav Kumar Nepal rejected the Maoist demand for his resignation, the former rebels have begun enforcing an indefinite general strike nationwide that has paralysed transport, businesses and industries and closed educational institutions.\n\nThough Maoist chief and former prime minister Pushpa Kamal Dahal Prachanda called the strike a dire necessity in order to \xe2\x80\x9cprotect the peace process, constitution and constituent assembly\xe2\x80\x9d, his young cadre, who had been herded in thousands from villages, were beginning to lose heart.\n\nDozens began to abandon the protests and head home. Some said they were unable to endure the inadequate food.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cWe have been living on dry beaten rice for days,\xe2\x80\x9d said a young man, who did not identify himself. \xe2\x80\x9cI can\xe2\x80\x99t stomach this any more.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\nAnother said he was tired of being incessantly ordered around.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cThey tell you to stand up and you have to stand up,\xe2\x80\x9d he said. \xe2\x80\x9cThen they tell you to sit down and you have to obey. There are orders to be followed throughout the day.\xe2\x80\x9d\n\nA group of deserters said they were farmers and needed to return home to plant and harvest the crops.\n\nOn May Day, Prachanda had boasted 500,000 people would be brought to Kathmandu. He had said they would camp in the capital indefinitely till their demands were met.\n\nHowever, the party that fought a guerrilla war for 10 years is now finding it far more difficult to sustain a peaceful protest.\n\nMany of the demonstrators are not dedicated workers but were simply rustled up from their homes under threat or blandishment.\n\nThey are now the first to leave after camping under a scorching sun with inadequate food, drinking water and shelter at night.\n\nGauri Pradhan, spokesman of the National Human Rights Commission, warned there was a grave fear of a diarrhoea outbreak in the capital with the thousands of protesters defecating in the open and increasing the risk of water supplies as well as crops and vegetables being contaminated.\n\nNearly 300 people died of diarrhoea last year while over 5,000 were affected in the districts outside the capital.\n\nThere were also growing public protests against the enforced strike.\n\nIn Chitwan in southern Nepal, farmers dumped their vegetables on the highway in protest while in Pokhara, a popular tourist destination, over two dozen people were hurt when sand miners resisted Maoist pressure to join their protests.\n\nSkirmishes were also reported in three areas in the capital as public resentment began to smoulder against both the Maoists and the government.\n\nDespite several rounds of talks, the two biggest ruling parties had failed to reach a negotiated settlement with the Maoists.\n\nThough another round of talks was underway Tuesday, people were beginning to lose hope and patience.\n\nEmbattled Prime Minister Madhav Kumar Nepal continued to reject the demand for his resignation, asking the Maoists to call off the strike first. ', 'Kathmandu, Central Region, Nepal | Diarrhea | Humans'
http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/politics/fear-of-epidemic-in-kathmandu-as-maoist-strike-enters-third-day_100358228.html

Whooping cough cases reported in San Luis Obispo County - Breaking ...
'\n\nCounty health officials are looking into several confirmed cases of whooping cough.\n\nThe respiratory infection, formally known as pertussis, ranges from mild to severe in adolescents and adults but can be fatal in infants, according to a news release from the San Luis Obispo County Public Health Department.\n\nSymptoms include a cough of increasing severity lasting more than two weeks and episodes of sudden coughing followed by vomiting. Infants afflicted with the infection may become pale or blue during a coughing episode, officials said.\n\nTreatment includes antibiotics and rest, although infants may need to be hospitalized.\n\nA pertussis vaccination is recommended for anyone who has close contact with an infant less than a year old. Those vaccines are available at the Public Health Department for $25.\n\nRead more: http://www.sanluisobispo.com/2010/04/30/1123804/whooping-cough-san-luis-obispo.html#ixzz0mzWyieTL\n ', 'San Luis Obispo County, California, United States | Whooping Cough | Humans'

u' \xbb 123 dengue fever patients found in Phuket\n 123 dengue fever patients found in Phuket \n Dr Narinrat Pichayakamin, a Public Health Doctor of Phuket, said that the rising temperature in Phuket had made an increase of dengue fever patients likely. From the beginning of the year, there were 123 dengue fever patients \n admitted into hospitals in the island. Respiratory Illness
Glengarry Hospital, Victoria, BC V8S 1G7, Canada
'48.415497','-123.332092',5,11614
CTV British Columbia - Tenth patient dies in outbreak at B.C. ...
'A 10th patient has died from an unidentified respiratory illness at Glengarry Hospital in Victoria, B.C.\n\nThat patient was a resident in the hospital\'s Fairfield unit, where two new cases of the mysterious illness were discovered last week, according to Vancouver Island Health Authority spokeswoman Shannon Marshall.\n\nThe respiratory symptoms first appeared in the hospital\'s Chandler Unit at the end of March, when an outbreak of the Norovirus was also underway. A total of nine elderly patients in that unit have died.\n\nIn all, 21 elderly hospital residents have fallen ill. Three staff members have also been sent home with symptoms of the illness, Marshall told ctvbc.ca.\n\nBut she said the illness doesn\'t appear to be spreading. "We have had no new cases since Friday."\n\nMedical reviews are now being conducted for the patients who have died, to determine what role the respiratory condition played in their deaths.\n\nThe health authority has described all of the patients who have died as "elderly and frail with multiple medical challenges," and at least five were already receiving palliative care.\n\nLab tests not yet been able to confirm what is causing the respiratory problems, but tests have ruled out influenza A and B and H1N1, as well as environmental causes and Legionnaire\'s disease.\n\nThe health authority is now asking family members of hospital residents to stay away from the hospital, especially if they are sick.\n\nThe hospital is also limiting contact between patients, serving residents\' meals in their rooms and requiring staff members and visitors to wear protective masks, gowns and gloves when visiting affected patients.  ', 'Glengarry Hospital, Victoria, BC V8S 1G7, Canada | Respiratory Illness | Humans', 'Glengarry Hospital, Victoria, BC V8S 1G7, Canada | Undiagnosed | Humans'
http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100504/bc_hospital_illness_100504/20100504?hub=BritishColumbia

' WHO: 15 deaths from Rift Valley fever in South Africa \nGeneva - The World Health Organization on Tuesday reported the first confirmed case of a traveller to South Africa contracting Rift Valley fever, which has already killed 15 people in the country. \nSince an outbreak began at the beginning of the year, a total of 172 people have been infected. \nThe German traveller visited rural areas and game reserves along the coast in the Eastern Cape and Western Cape provinces, the WHO said in a disease update note. ['<img class=\\"f\\" src=\\"..\\/w\\" title=\\"World Health Organization\\" alt=\\"World Health Organization\\" \\/>', '4 May 2010', '<a href=\\"..\\/ai.php?420808&trto=en&trfr=en&pid101\\" class=\\"fbox\\">Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update<\\/a>', 'Rift Valley Fever', '<a href=\\"javascript:sc(\'51.106560\',\'10.393650\',5,101);\\">Germany<\\/a>', 'Humans', '1', 'null']
4
420808

World Health Organization
4 May 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Germany
'51.106560','10.393650',5,101
Rift Valley fever in South Africa- update
' As of 3 May 2010, the Department of Health of South Africa has reported 172 cases, including 15 deaths since the beginning of the outbreak in Free State Province, Eastern Cape Province, Northern Cape Province, Western Cape, and North West Province. While it is reported that most of these cases have had direct contact with RVF-infected livestock and/or are epidemiologically linked to farms with confirmed animal cases of RVF, there are a number of cases in which the route of transmission is currently unknown. Exposure to infected mosquitoes in these cases cannot be currently ruled out.  The Government of South Africa has implemented public health control measures which include development of key risk reduction messages for at risk population and health worker guidelines for case identification and reporting, laboratory investigations, clinical case management, hospital infection control and the public health measures for prevention and control and animal vaccination in non-affected areas. WHO advises no international travel restriction to or from South Africa. However, WHO recommends that visitors to South Africa, especially those intending to visit farms and/or game reserves, avoid coming into contact with animal tissues or blood, avoid drinking unpasteurized or uncooked milk or eating raw meat. All travellers should take appropriate precautions against mosquito bites (use of mosquito nets, insect repellents). Travel medicine professionals and travel medicine services should be aware of the current RVF situation in South Africa in order to provide advice and care accordingly. For more information Department of Health, South Africa    The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)   Robert Koch Institute   Rift Valley fever: WHO fact sheet   Protection against vectors [pdf 548kb]International Travel and Health  ', 'Germany | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.who.int/entity/csr/don/2010_05_04a/en/index.html

'46.346901','48.032200',5,415
Suspected Food Poisoning Sickens Dozens Of Children In Russia's ...
" Gedmin and Mikheil Saakashvili discussed business and political reforms in Georgia at the Milken Institute's Global Conference in Los Angeles. More \n News \n ASTRAKHAN, Russia -- Dozens of schoolchildren have been hospitalized with apparent food poisoning in the Astrakhan oblast of Russia's Volga region, RFE/RL's Russian Service reports. The 39 children -- aged between eight and 14 -- are students at the same school in the village of Tuzuklei. The first patients were referred to a doctor on April 30, followed by others over the weekend. Local police have launched an investigation into the incident. Officials in Astrakhan Oblast said they would make public later today the results of laboratory tests on the school's meals. \n Editors' Picks \n John O'Sullivan On Britain's Hotly Contested Elections  ", 'Astrakhan | Foodborne Illness | Humans'

Children's cold, allergy medicine recalled - CNN.com
' Children\'s Motrin, Tylenol among drugs being recalled for failing to meet quality standards Recall not based on adverse health effects, company says Drugs were made in United States, distributed to other countries \n (CNN) \n -- A voluntary recall has been issued for more than 40 over-the-counter drugs for children, including Tylenol and Motrin, because they don\'t meet quality standards. \n"This recall is not being undertaken on the basis of adverse medical events," McNeil Consumer Healthcare said in a statement Friday. "However, as a precautionary measure, parents and caregivers should not administer these products to their children." \nFDA commissioner Margaret Hamburg gave a similar recommendation in a statement Saturday, saying, "we want to be certain that consumers discontinue using these products," though she called the chance for serious health problems "remote." Saudi Gazette - Who\u2019s responsible for the dengue outbreak?
u' Sunday, 02 May 2010 \xa0-\xa0 18 Jumada Al-Awwal 1431 H \n Who\xe2\x80\x99s responsible for the dengue outbreak? \n JEDDAH \u2013 A day after five government agencies met to discuss ways to combat an outbreak of dengue fever \u2013 which has already infected hundreds of people - officials from the mayoralty and the health affairs department started blaming each other for the situation. The meeting took place Saturday and was meant to come up with solutions; instead a war of words has broken out between officials from the two government bodies. Over 200 people contracted the disease over the past two weeks. A total of 750 cases over the past 16 weeks have been confirmed. The Directorate of Health Affairs accused the mayoralty of ignoring its warning that it should deal with the breeding grounds of disease carriers. The mayoralty replied that the information provided by Health Affairs officials did not accurately reflect the magnitude of the problem, which affected the response to the disease. Bassam Akhdhar, member of the Municipal Council in Jeddah, said that he held the Ministry of Health and the mayoralty accountable for the increase in dengue fever cases. He also accused cleaning companies in Jeddah for not cleaning up heaps of garbage in southern and central Jeddah. He said it was a common sight to see the dirt and waste around the buildings and residential areas in these districts. He claimed that the emergency plan was \u201cnothing but ink on paper\u201d because it was not being implemented. He also expressed doubts about the authenticity and accuracy of the information provided by the Ministry of Health. He said this alleged inaccurate information aggravated the problem in Jeddah and was a reflection of the weak response to combating the disease. He called on the Directorate of Health Affairs and Jeddah Mayoralty to stop blaming each other because this will not solve the problem. He said residents were the ones suffering. \u2013 Okaz/SG \n Judges reject time limit for resolving cases \n Father tragically loses four children  ', 'Saudi Arabia | Dengue | Humans'
